{"title_page": "1991 World Championships in Athletics", "text_new": "{{World Championships in Athletics\n|Name =3rd World Championships in Athletics\n|Logo = Tokyo IAAF 1991.jpg\n|Size =\n|Host city =[[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n|Optional caption =\n|Nations participating =167\n|Athletes participating =1517\n|Events =\n|dates =August 23 \u2013 September 1\n|Officially opened by  =  [[Emperor of Japan|Emperor]] [[Akihito]]\n|Stadium =[[Olympic Stadium, Tokyo|Olympic Stadium]]\n|previous = [[1987 World Championships in Athletics|1987 Rome]]\n|next = [[1993 World Championships in Athletics|1993 Stuttgart]]\n}}\n\nThe '''3rd [[IAAF World Championships in Athletics|World Championships in Athletics]]''', under the auspices of the [[International Association of Athletics Federations]], were held in the [[Olympic Stadium, Tokyo|Olympic Stadium]] in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]] between August 23 and September 1 and athletes from 167 countries participated in the event.<ref>{{cite web|title=iaaf.org - Osaka 2007 - History |url=http://osaka2007.iaaf.org/history/index.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312032624/http://osaka2007.iaaf.org/history/index.html |archivedate=2009-03-12 |url-status=dead |accessdate=2009-04-03 }}</ref>\n\nThe event is best-remembered for the men's [[long jump]] competition, when [[Carl Lewis]] made the best six-jump series in history, only to be beaten by [[Mike Powell (long jumper)|Mike Powell]], whose {{convert|8.95|m|ftin|2|abbr=on}} jump broke [[Bob Beamon]]'s long-standing world record from the [[1968 Summer Olympics]].\n\n==Men's results==\n\n===Track===\n[[1983 World Championships in Athletics#Track|1983]] | [[1987 World Championships in Athletics#Track|1987]] | 1991 | [[1993 World Championships in Athletics#Track|1993]] | [[1995 World Championships in Athletics#Track|1995]]\n{| {{MedalistTable|columns=2}}\n|-\n|100 m<br>{{DetailsLink|1991 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 100 metres}}\n|{{flagathlete|[[Carl Lewis]]|USA}}||9.86<br><s