.iaaf.org/history/index.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312032624/http://osaka2007.iaaf.org/history/index.html |archivedate=2009-03-12 |url-status=dead |accessdate=2009-04-03 }}</ref>\n\nThe event is best-remembered for the men's [[long jump]] competition, when [[Carl Lewis]] made the best six-jump series in history, only to be beaten by [[Mike Powell (long jumper)|Mike Powell]], whose {{convert|8.95|m|ftin|2|abbr=on}} jump broke [[Bob Beamon]]'s long-standing world record from the [[1968 Summer Olympics]].\n\n==Men's results==\n\n===Track===\n[[1983 World Championships in Athletics#Track|1983]] | [[1987 World Championships in Athletics#Track|1987]] | 1991 | [[1993 World Championships in Athletics#Track|1993]] | [[1995 World Championships in Athletics#Track|1995]]\n{| {{MedalistTable|columns=2}}\n|-\n|100 m<br>{{DetailsLink|1991 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 100 metres}}\n|{{flagathlete|[[Carl Lewis]]|USA}}||9.86<br><small>('''WR''')</small>\n|{{flagathlete|[[Leroy Burrell]]|USA}}||9.88<br><small>(PB)</small>\n|{{flagathlete|[[Dennis Mitchell]]|USA}}||9.91<br><small>(PB)</small>\n|-\n|200 m<br>{{DetailsLink|1991 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 200 metres}}\n|{{flagathlete|[[Michael Johnson (athlete)|Michael Johnson]]|USA}}||20.01<br><small>('''CR''')</small>\n|{{flagathlete|[[Frankie Fredericks]]|NAM}}||20.34\n|{{flagathlete|[[Atlee Mahorn]]|CAN}}||20.49\n|-\n|400 m<br>{{DetailsLink|1991 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 400 metres}}\n|{{flagathlete|[[Antonio Pettigrew]]|USA}}||44.57\n|{{flagathlete|[[Roger Black]]|GBR}}||44.62\n|{{flagathlete|[[Danny Everett]]|USA}}||44.63\n|-\n|800 m<br>{{DetailsLink|1991 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 800 metres}}\n|{{flagathlete|[[Billy Konchellah]]|KEN}}||1:43.99\n|{{flagathlete|[[Jos\u00e9 Lu\u00edz Barbosa]]|BRA|1968}}||1:44.24\n|{{flagathlete|[[Mark Everett (athlete)|Mark Everett]]|USA}}||1:44.67\n|-\n|1500 m<br>{{DetailsLink|1991 World Championships 