{"title_page": "Albert Elms", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n'''Albert Elms''' (28 February 1920 &ndash; 14 October 2009) was a [[UK|British]] [[composer]] and arranger who worked mainly for television and film.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/albert-elms-light-music-composer-7ml2nndf03d|title=Albert Elms: light music composer|date=11 November 2009|work=The Times|access-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlbert Elms was born in [[Newington, Swale|Newington]], [[Kent]], [[England]], and died in [[Southampton]]. He joined the Royal Marine Band Service at Deal in 1934, took part in the Vaagso raid in 1940 and served on the Malta Convoys in 1941-42.\n\nAfter Albert left the Royal Marines he joined Francis,Day and Hunter, a music publishing company.<ref name=\":0\" /> His break into television came with the launch of commercial television in Britain during 1955. He made a contribution to [[ITV Network|ITV]]'s ''[[The Adventures of Robin Hood (TV series)|The Adventures of Robin Hood]]'' (1955\u201359) with [[Richard Greene]] in the lead, writing the musical scores for at least two series.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Perry|first=Chris|url=|title=The Kaleidoscope British Christmas Television Guide 1937-2013|last2=Coward|first2=Simon|last3=Down|first3=Richard|publisher=Kaleidoscope Publishing|year=2013|isbn=978-1-900203-60-9|location=Handsworth Wood, United Kingdom|pages=17}}</ref> He also wrote musical scores for ''[[The Buccaneers (TV series)|The Buccaneers]]'' (1956\u201357), starring [[Robert Shaw (British actor)|Robert Shaw]], ''[[The Adventures of Sir Lancelot]]'' (1956\u201357), starring [[William Russell (English actor)|William Russell]], and ''[[Ivanhoe (1958 TV series)|Ivanhoe]]'' (1958\u201359) with [[Roger Moore]]. However, he is best known for providing incidental music for later [[Incorporated Television Company|ITC]] series such as ''[[Man in a Suitcase]]'' (1967\u201368), ''[[The Champions]]'' (1968-69) and for 14 of the 17 episodes of ''[[The Prisoner]]'' (1967\u201368) starring [[Patrick McGoohan]].\n\nAlthough the series on which Albert did most work had memorable main title scores by others such as [[Ron Grainer]] and [[Tony Hatch]], he provided cues which represent hundreds of hours of music. His contribution has recently been recognised with the release of his complete incidental music for ''Man in a Suitcase'' on CD.\n\nOn occasions he also wrote complete film scores for movies such as ''[[Satellite in the Sky]]'' (1956), ''[[The Man Without a Body]]'' (1957), ''[[On the Run (1958 film)|On the Run]]'' (1958), ''[[Bluebeard's Ten Honeymoons]]'' (1960), ''[[The Breaking Point (1961 film)|The Breaking Point]]'' (1961), ''[[The Omegans]]'' (1968), and the film version of ''[[Love Thy Neighbour (1973 film)|Love Thy Neighbour]]'' (1973).\n\nHe also served as musical director of ''[[The Benny Hill Show]]'' for three episodes of the 1973\u201374 season,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/dec/10/television|title=Albert Elms obituary|last=Gaughan|first=Gavin|date=|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> substituting for [[Ronnie Aldrich]]. He wrote the Corps quick march, ''On Parade'', for The Royal Logistic Corps which formed in 1993. He lived for more than 40 years at the family home in the village of Oad Street near Borden in Kent.\n\nAlbert Elms had three sons, Martin, David, and Jeremy. His wife Jo predeceased him in 1990.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Empty section|date=January 2019}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0255482}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elms, Albert}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:English film score composers]]\n[[Category:English television composers]]\n[[Category:English male composers]]\n[[Category:People from Milton, Kent]]\n[[Category:Royal Marines]]\n[[Category:Royal Marines personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Kent]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n'''Albert Elms''' (28 February 1920 &ndash; 14 October 2009) was a [[UK|British]] [[composer]] and arranger who worked mainly for television and film.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/albert-elms-light-music-composer-7ml2nndf03d|title=Albert Elms: light music composer|date=11 November 2009|work=The Times|access-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlbert Elms was born in [[Newington, Swale|Newington]], [[Kent]], [[England]], and died in [[Southampton]]. He joined the Royal Marine Band Service at Deal in 1934, took part in the Vaagso raid in 1940 and served on the Malta Convoys in 1941-42.\n\nAfter Albert left the Royal Marines he joined Francis,Day and Hunter, a music publishing company.<ref name=\":0\" /> His break into television came with the launch of commercial television in Britain during 1955. He made a contribution to [[ITV Network|ITV]]'s ''[[The Adventures of Robin Hood (TV series)|The Adventures of Robin Hood]]'' (1955\u201359) with [[Richard Greene]] in the lead, writing the musical scores for at least two series.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Perry|first=Chris|url=|title=The Kaleidoscope British Christmas Television Guide 1937-2013|last2=Coward|first2=Simon|last3=Down|first3=Richard|publisher=Kaleidoscope Publishing|year=2013|isbn=978-1-900203-60-9|location=Handsworth Wood, United Kingdom|pages=17}}</ref> He also wrote musical scores for ''[[The Buccaneers (TV series)|The Buccaneers]]'' (1956\u201357), starring [[Robert Shaw (British actor)|Robert Shaw]], ''[[The Adventures of Sir Lancelot]]'' (1956\u201357), starring [[William Russell (English actor)|William Russell]], and ''[[Ivanhoe (1958 TV series)|Ivanhoe]]'' (1958\u201359) with [[Roger Moore]]. However, he is best known for providing incidental music for later [[Incorporated Television Company|ITC]] series such as ''[[Man in a Suitcase]]'' (1967\u201368), ''[[The Champions]]'' (1968-69) and for 14 of the 17 episodes of ''[[The Prisoner]]'' (1967\u201368) starring [[Patrick McGoohan]].\n\nAlthough the series on which Albert did most work had memorable main title scores by others such as [[Ron Grainer]] and [[Tony Hatch]], he provided cues which represent hundreds of hours of music. His contribution has recently been recognised with the release of his complete incidental music for ''Man in a Suitcase'' on CD.\n\nOn occasions he also wrote complete film scores for movies such as ''[[Satellite in the Sky]]'' (1956), ''[[The Man Without a Body]]'' (1957), ''[[On the Run (1958 film)|On the Run]]'' (1958), ''[[Bluebeard's Ten Honeymoons]]'' (1960), ''[[The Breaking Point (1961 film)|The Breaking Point]]'' (1961), ''[[The Omegans]]'' (1968), and the film version of ''[[Love Thy Neighbour (1973 film)|Love Thy Neighbour]]'' (1973).\n\nHe also served as musical director of ''[[The Benny Hill Show]]'' for three episodes of the 1973\u201374 season,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/dec/10/television|title=Albert Elms obituary|last=Gaughan|first=Gavin|date=|website=The Guardina|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> substituting for [[Ronnie Aldrich]]. He wrote the Corps quick march, ''On Parade'', for The Royal Logistic Corps which formed in 1993. He lived for more than 40 years at the family home in the village of Oad Street near Borden in Kent.\n\nAlbert Elms had three sons, Martin, David, and Jeremy. His wife Jo predeceased him in 1990.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Empty section|date=January 2019}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0255482}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elms, Albert}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:English film score composers]]\n[[Category:English television composers]]\n[[Category:English male composers]]\n[[Category:People from Milton, Kent]]\n[[Category:Royal Marines]]\n[[Category:Royal Marines personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Kent]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n", "name_user": "Videodragons", "label": "safe", "comment": "Misspelling of \"Guardian\". Tut tut. :)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Elms"}
{"title_page": "Tom Moore (fundraiser)", "text_new": "{{short description|British Army Officer and fundraiser}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n| name               = Tom Moore\n| image              = Tom Moore (soldier).jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Moore during his military service\n| birth_name         = Thomas Moore\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1920|4|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Keighley]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]], United Kingdom\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = British\n| residence          = [[Marston Moretaine]], [[Bedfordshire]]\n| education          = \n| alma mater         = \n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n* Army officer\n* Managing director \n}}\n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| known for          = {{Plainlist|\n* Second World War veteran\n* 2020 fundraising walk\n}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Keighley Grammar School]], West Yorkshire\n| boards             = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = 2\n| parents            = \n| relations          = \n| website            = {{URL|https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs|tomswalkforthenhs}}\n| module = {{Infobox military person |embed=yes\n   | allegiance  = {{GBR}}\n   |branch       = {{flagicon image|Flag of the British Army (1938-present).png}} [[British Army]]\n   |serviceyears = 1939\u20131946\n   |rank         = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n   |unit         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment]]\n* [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n* [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n}}\n   |commands     = \n   |battles           = {{tree list}}\n*[[World War II|Second World War]]\n**[[Burma campaign 1944\u201345|Burma Campaign]]\n***[[Battle of Ramree Island]]\n   |awards = \n  }}\n}}\n'''Thomas Moore''' (born 30 April 1920), known as '''Captain Tom''', is a former [[British Army]] officer, best known for his philanthropic work. Moore served in India and the [[Burma campaign]] during the [[Second World War]]. He later became an instructor in [[armoured warfare]]. After the war, he worked as managing director of a concrete company and was an avid motorcycle racer. On 6 April 2020, at the age of 99, he began to walk around his garden in aid of [[NHS Charities Together]] during the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic]], with the goal of raising \u00a31,000 by his hundredth birthday on 30 April. By 19 April he had raised over \u00a326.2<!-- please update the figure in two places and the date/timestamp -->&nbsp;million.\n\n==Early life and family==\n\nMoore was born to Wilfred, one of a family of builders, in [[Keighley]], in the former [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], on 30 April 1920 and was raised in the town.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Faye |title=The story behind the 99-year-old legend who raised \u00a314m for the NHS |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/16/tom-moore-story-behind-14000000-nhs-legend-12565964/ |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Metro |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.strayfm.com/news/local-news/3082429/coronavirus-veteran-from-keighley-raises-over-2-million-for-nhs/|title=Coronavirus: Veteran from Keighley raises over \u00a32 MILLION for NHS|date=14 April 2020|publisher=Stray FM|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/apr/14/war-veteran-99-raises-2m-for-nhs-by-walking-lengths-of-back-garden|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36m for NHS by walking lengths of back garden|first=Jessica|last=Murray|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Guardian}}</ref> He was educated at [[Keighley Grammar School]] and completed an apprenticeship in [[civil engineering]].<ref name=\"Nicholls\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/04/14/second-world-war-veteran-raises-2-million-nhs/ |title=Second World War veteran raises more than \u00a33m for NHS |first=Dominic |last=Nicholls |date=14 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\nMoore  enlisted in the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment#8th Battalion|8th Battalion, Duke of Wellington's Regiment]] (8&nbsp;DWR) at the beginning of the [[Second World War]], stationed in [[Cornwall]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> He was selected for officer training in 1940,<ref name=\"Nicholls\" />  and attended an Officer Cadet Training Unit before being commissioned as a [[second lieutenant#United Kingdom & other Commonwealth countries|second lieutenant]] on 28&nbsp;June 1941.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35218|date=11 July 1941|page=4057|supp=y}}</ref>\n\nMoore became a member of the [[Royal Armoured Corps]] on 22 October 1941 when his battalion, the 8&nbsp;DWR, became an armoured unit, designated as the [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35740|date=9 October 1942|page=4432|supp=y}}</ref><ref name=\"Nicholls\"/> Later he was transferred to the 9th&nbsp;Battalion (9&nbsp;DWR) in India, which had also been redesignated as the [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]. He was initially posted to [[Bombay]] and subsequently to [[Calcutta]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> His regiment were equipped with [[M3 Lee]] tanks and participated in the [[Battle of Ramree Island]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Whiting |first1=Charles |last2=Taylor |first2=Eric |date=2008 |title=The Fighting Tykes: An Informal History of the Yorkshire Regiments in the Second World War |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9kt-AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA132 |publisher=Pen & Sword Military |page=132 |isbn=978-1844156450}}</ref> He was promoted to war-substantive [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] on 1&nbsp;October 1942 and to temporary [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 11&nbsp;October 1944.<ref>{{cite book |date=1946 |title=The Quarterly Army List (August 1946 \u2013 Part I) |location=London |publisher=HM Stationery Office |isbn= |pages=385a |url=https://archive.org/details/armylistaugpart121946grea/page/398/mode/2up|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe served in [[Arakan]] in western Burma and afterward in [[Sumatra]] after the [[Surrender of Japan|Japanese surrender]],<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52278746|title=Army veteran, 99, raises \u00a34m for 'humbled' NHS|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref> by which time he had risen to the rank of captain.<ref name=\"Nicholls\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/> On his return to Britain he served as an instructor at the Armoured Fighting Vehicle School in [[Bovington Camp|Bovington]], Dorset.<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/>\n\n=== Decorations ===\n\nFor his war service, Moore was awarded three medals:<ref name=\"ES\">{{cite news |title=War veteran, 99, hits \u00a314m for NHS as Hancock calls him an inspiration |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/war-veteran-tom-moore-matt-hancock-9-million-nhs-a4415496.html |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n*[[1939\u20131945 Star]]\n*[[Burma Star]]\n*[[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]\n\n== Later work and hobbies ==\n\nAfter leaving the army, he worked as managing director of a company manufacturing [[concrete]].<ref name=\"Spary\" />\n\nFor 64 years he organised the DWR's annual reunion.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\nMoore raced motorcycles competitively, wearing the number 23.<ref name=\"Hancocks\">{{cite web |last1=Hancocks |first1=Simon |title=Veteran NHS fundraiser Captain Tom Moore was also a motorcycle racer |url=https://www.visordown.com/news/general/veteran-nhs-fundraiser-captain-tom-moore-was-also-motorcycle-racer |website=Visordown |accessdate=17 April 2020 }}</ref> He rode a [[The Scott Motorcycle Company|Scott motorcycle]], winning several trophies.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\n== Tom's 100th Birthday Walk  ==\n[[File:Captain Tom Moore fundraising walk.jpg|thumb|upright|Moore during the fund-raising initiative walk. He is wearing the [[1939\u20131945 Star]], [[Burma Star]], and [[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]. |alt=Moore wearing a blazer with regimental badge, regimental tie and three medals]]\n\nOn 6 April 2020 he began a fundraising campaign to raise money for [[NHS Charities Together]], a group of charities supporting staff and volunteers caring for COVID-19 patients in the British public health services during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] by aiming to complete one hundred {{convert|25|m|yard|abbr=on}} laps of his garden, ten laps per day, with the help of a [[Walker (mobility)|walking frame]], branding the endeavour \"'''Tom's 100th Birthday Walk For The NHS'''\".<ref name=\"Spary\" /><ref name=\"Low\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52290976\">{{cite web |title=Army veteran's \u00a37m for NHS 'out of this world' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52290976 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe initial \u00a31,000 goal having been realised on Friday 10 April, the target was increased, first to \u00a35,000, and eventually to \u00a3500,000 as more people around the world became involved.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/nhs-100-birthday-walk-army-veteran-tom-moore-fundraise-a9463561.html |title=99-year-old army veteran raises more than \u00a31m for NHS with \u2018100th birthday walk\u2019 |date=14 April 2020 |work=The Independent |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> The fund-raising soared exponentially when the British media publicised the endeavour. Moore, who joined [[Twitter]] in the same month, used the site to express joy over accumulating such a staggering amount of money for the NHS.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=CaptainTomMoore |number=1250418629218168833 |date=15 April 2020 |title=7 MILLION POUNDS!!!! The Great British public, your generosity is just incredible! THANK YOU!! }}</ref> \n\nThe [[JustGiving]] page for his walk reports that, as of 19:00 19 April 2020 (UTC), he had raised in excess of \u00a326.2<!-- please update the figure in two places and the date/ timestamp-->&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"JGTM\">{{cite web |title=Captain Tom Moore's 100th Birthday Walk for the NHS |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs |publisher=[[JustGiving]] |accessdate=19 April 2020 }}</ref> the largest-ever amount raised by a JustGiving campaign,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792|title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |website=inews.co.uk| access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-18098819|title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard|last=Shaw|first=Neil|date=2020-04-16|website=walesonline|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> beating the previous record of \u00a35.2&nbsp;million raised (partially posthumously) by [[Stephen Sutton]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Stephen's fundraising page |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/stephen-sutton-tct |website=JustGiving |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Butterworth\">{{cite news |last1=Butterworth |first1=Benjamin |title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=inews.co.uk }}</ref> More than 1.2 million individuals have donated.<ref name=\"JGTM\" />\n\nFunds raised by Moore are being spent on such things as well-being packs for National Health Service staff facilitating rest and recuperation rooms, devices to enable hospital patients to keep in contact with family members, and community groups who support patients once discharged from hospitals.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52325713\">{{cite web |last1=Shepka |first1=Phil |last2=Lewis |first2=Katy |title=How will Captain Tom Moore's millions be spent? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52325713 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=18 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe achieved his initial target of one hundred laps on the morning of 16 April, watched [[Social distancing measures related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|at a safe distance]] by a [[guard of honour]] from the [[1st Battalion, The Yorkshire Regiment|1st Battalion of the Yorkshire Regiment]],<ref name=\"Shaw\">{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Neil |title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard |url=https://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-4050824 |work=hulldailymail |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> into which the DWR were merged in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx |title=The Yorkshire Regiment |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence]] |archivedate=27 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527064813/http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx }}</ref> He has said he will not stop, and aims to do a second hundred.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" />\n\nOn reaching the \u00a35&nbsp;million mark, Moore explained his motivation:<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-52296313/coronavirus-army-veteran-tom-moore-finds-out-he-s-raised-5m-for-nhs |title=Army veteran, 99, finds out he's raised \u00a35m for NHS |publisher=BBC News |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|When we started off with this exercise we didn't anticipate we'd get anything near that sort of money. It's really amazing. All of them, from top to bottom, in the National Health Service, they deserve everything that we can possibly put in their place. They're all so brave. Because every morning or every night they're putting themselves into harm's way, and I think you've got to give them full marks for that effort. We're a little bit like having a war at the moment. But the doctors and the nurses, they're all on the front line, and all of us behind, we've got to supply them and keep them going with everything that they need, so that they can do their jobs even better than they're doing now.}}\n\n=== Charity recording ===\n\nTo mark Moore's 100th lap, the singer [[Michael Ball]] has recorded a version of \"[[You'll Never Walk Alone]]\", with the NHS Voices of Care Choir, and featuring Moore's spoken words.<ref name=\"ITV\">{{cite news |title=Captain Tom Moore launches You'll Never Walk Alone charity single with Michael Ball |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-18/captain-tom-moore-launches-you-ll-never-walk-alone-charity-single-with-michael-ball/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=ITV News }}</ref> The recording has been released as a digital single by Decca Records.<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web |title=You'll Never Walk Alone - Single by Michael Ball, Captain Tom Moore & The NHS Voices of Care Choir |url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/youll-never-walk-alone/1508494673?i=1508494683&uo=2 |publisher=Apple Music |accessdate=19 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n=== Recognition ===\n\nMoore has given well over 50 media interviews.<ref name=\"BBC-52333127\">{{cite web |title=Capt Tom 'speechless' as fundraising passes \u00a323m |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52333127 |website=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, after Moore's 100th lap, a UK Government spokesman said:<ref name=\"Lovett\">{{cite news |last1=Lovett |first1=Samuel |title=UK death toll rises again as lockdown to be extended \u2013 follow live |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-news-live-update-latest-today-cases-deaths-lockdown-covid-19-a9467756.html#post-1187989853 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The Prime Minister will certainly be looking at ways to recognise Tom's heroic efforts.}}\n\nBy midday on 17 April, more than 505,000 people had signed a petition calling for him to be knighted.<ref name=\"BBC-52321262\">{{cite news |title=Prince William hails veteran's \u00a318m NHS fundraiser |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52321262 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBrigadier Andrew Jackson, colonel of the Yorkshire Regiment, described Moore as:<ref name=\"BBC-52340554\">{{cite web |title=Capt Tom to be guest of honour at hospital opening |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-52340554 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|an absolute legend [from] an exceptional generation that are still an inspiration for our Yorkshire soldiers today.}}\n\nKeighley Town Council stated that they grant Moore the [[Freedom of the City|Freedom of Keighley]].<ref name=\"ITV-freedom\">{{cite web |title=Veteran Capt Tom Moore to be given freedom of Keighley after raising \u00a313m for NHS |url=https://www.itv.com/news/calendar/2020-04-16/veteran-capt-tom-moore-to-be-given-freedom-of-keighley-after-raising-13m-for-nhs/ |publisher=ITV News |accessdate=19 April 2020 }}</ref> Moore has also been invited to be guest of honour, via a video link, when [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Yorkshire and the Humber]], in [[Harrogate]], is formally opened on 21 April.<ref name=\"BBC-52340554\" />\n\n===Similar fundraising efforts===\nMoore's success inspired retired Welsh farmer Rhythwyn Evans to launch his own fundraising campaign<ref name=\"JGDE\">{{cite web|title=Her 91 dros COVID-19 Rhythwyn|url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/david-evans186|quote=91st birthday challenge to support local NHS staff for Hywel Dda Health Charities because of their hard work during COVID-19|publisher=Just Giving|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> by walking 91 laps of his bungalow in [[Silian, Ceredigion|Silian]], [[Ceredigion]], on his 91st birthday on 18 April 2020. Evans said that his walk was \"inspired by and in solidarity with Captain Tom Moore\" and that he aimed to raise \u00a31,000 for his local health board \"to give something back to the community\", having lived to a \"ripe old age\". Evans completed the laps before 17:30 and quipped that his next aim was to get \"a good night's sleep!\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/18/welsh-farmer-doing-91-laps-of-bungalow-on-91st-birthday-for-nhs-coronavirus|title=Welsh farmer doing 91 laps of his bungalow on 91st birthday for NHS|publisher=The Guardian|date=18 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-04-19/farmer-91-walks-91-laps-of-his-home-to-raise-funds-for-the-nhs/|title=Farmer, 91, walks 91 laps of his home to raise funds for the NHS|publisher=ITV News|date=19 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> As of 16:00 on 19 April 2020 (UTC), Evans has raised over \u00a329,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/uk-news/2020/04/18/grandfather-walks-91-laps-around-bungalow-on-91st-birthday-to-raise-cash-for-nhs/ |title=Grandfather walks 91 laps around bungalow on 91st birthday to raise cash for NHS|publisher=Shropshire Star|date=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-wales-52333077/coronavirus-capt-tom-moore-inspires-91-year-old-s-walk-for-nhs|title=Coronavirus: Capt Tom Moore inspires 91-year-old's walk for NHS |publisher=BBC News |date=17 April 2020 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMoore married Pamela in 1968,<ref name=\"Lavender\">{{cite news |last1=Lavender |first1=Jane |title=Captain Tom Moore had 'given up on love' before he met beloved late wife aged 50 |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-given-up-21876074 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=mirror |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> and they had two daughters.<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> Pamela died circa 2006.<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> He has lived with one of his daughters, Hannah, her husband, and two grandchildren, in [[Marston Moretaine]], [[Bedfordshire]] since 2008.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /> He also has two other grandchildren.<ref name=\"Brown\" /> In recent years he has received treatment from the NHS for skin cancer and, in 2018, a broken hip.<ref name=\"Brown\" /><ref name=\"Low\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/captain-tom-moore-99-walks-to-raise-millions-for-the-nhs-fzpn0cjfb|title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, raises \u00a35m for NHS with 100th birthday walk|first=Valentine|last=Low|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/99-year-old-army-veteran-raises-2-million-charity-walking-his-backyard-1497742|title=99-year-old army veteran raises $2 million for charity by walking in his backyard|first=Khaleda | last=Rahman|date=14 April 2020|website=Newsweek|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spary\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/14/world/war-veteran-raises-millions-garden-scli-intl-gbr/index.html|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36 million by walking laps of his garden|first=Sara |last=Spary|website=CNN|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs Moore's fund-raising page]\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{YouTube|wUP-ty-Tj5E|You'll Never Walk Alone}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52316856 Captain Tom Moore: How the war veteran captured our hearts] \u2013 BBC news\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Tom}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Charity events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Duke of Wellington's Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:English civil engineers]]\n[[Category:People from Keighley]]\n[[Category:Skin cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Royal Armoured Corps officers]]\n[[Category:English motorcycle racers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Army Officer and fundraiser}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n| name               = Tom Moore\n| image              = Tom Moore (soldier).jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Moore during his military service\n| birth_name         = Thomas Moore\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1920|4|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Keighley]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]], United Kingdom\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = British\n| residence          = [[Marston Moretaine]], [[Bedfordshire]]\n| education          = \n| alma mater         = \n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n* Army officer\n* Managing director \n}}\n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| known for          = {{Plainlist|\n* Second World War veteran\n* 2020 fundraising walk\n}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Keighley Grammar School]], West Yorkshire\n| boards             = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = 2\n| parents            = \n| relations          = \n| website            = {{URL|https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs|tomswalkforthenhs}}\n| module = {{Infobox military person |embed=yes\n   | allegiance  = {{GBR}}\n   |branch       = {{flagicon image|Flag of the British Army (1938-present).png}} [[British Army]]\n   |serviceyears = 1939\u20131946\n   |rank         = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n   |unit         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment]]\n* [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n* [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n}}\n   |commands     = \n   |battles           = {{tree list}}\n*[[World War II|Second World War]]\n**[[Burma campaign 1944\u201345|Burma Campaign]]\n***[[Battle of Ramree Island]]\n   |awards = \n  }}\n}}\n'''Thomas Moore''' (born 30 April 1920), known as '''Captain Tom''', is a former [[British Army]] officer, best known for his philanthropic work. Moore served in India and the [[Burma campaign]] during the [[Second World War]]. He later became an instructor in [[armoured warfare]]. After the war, he worked as managing director of a concrete company and was an avid motorcycle racer. On 6 April 2020, at the age of 99, he began to walk around his garden in aid of [[NHS Charities Together]] during the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic]], with the goal of raising \u00a31,000 by his hundredth birthday on 30 April. By 19 April he had raised over \u00a326.2<!-- please update the figure in two places and the date/timestamp -->&nbsp;million.\n\n==Early life and family==\n\nMoore was born to Wilfred, one of a family of builders, in [[Keighley]], in the former [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], on 30 April 1920 and was raised in the town.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Faye |title=The story behind the 99-year-old legend who raised \u00a314m for the NHS |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/16/tom-moore-story-behind-14000000-nhs-legend-12565964/ |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Metro |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.strayfm.com/news/local-news/3082429/coronavirus-veteran-from-keighley-raises-over-2-million-for-nhs/|title=Coronavirus: Veteran from Keighley raises over \u00a32 MILLION for NHS|date=14 April 2020|publisher=Stray FM|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/apr/14/war-veteran-99-raises-2m-for-nhs-by-walking-lengths-of-back-garden|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36m for NHS by walking lengths of back garden|first=Jessica|last=Murray|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Guardian}}</ref> He was educated at [[Keighley Grammar School]] and completed an apprenticeship in [[civil engineering]].<ref name=\"Nicholls\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/04/14/second-world-war-veteran-raises-2-million-nhs/ |title=Second World War veteran raises more than \u00a33m for NHS |first=Dominic |last=Nicholls |date=14 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\nMoore  enlisted in the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment#8th Battalion|8th Battalion, Duke of Wellington's Regiment]] (8&nbsp;DWR) at the beginning of the [[Second World War]], stationed in [[Cornwall]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> He was selected for officer training in 1940,<ref name=\"Nicholls\" />  and attended an Officer Cadet Training Unit before being commissioned as a [[second lieutenant#United Kingdom & other Commonwealth countries|second lieutenant]] on 28&nbsp;June 1941.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35218|date=11 July 1941|page=4057|supp=y}}</ref>\n\nMoore became a member of the [[Royal Armoured Corps]] on 22 October 1941 when his battalion, the 8&nbsp;DWR, became an armoured unit, designated as the [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35740|date=9 October 1942|page=4432|supp=y}}</ref><ref name=\"Nicholls\"/> Later he was transferred to the 9th&nbsp;Battalion (9&nbsp;DWR) in India, which had also been redesignated as the [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]. He was initially posted to [[Bombay]] and subsequently to [[Calcutta]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> His regiment were equipped with [[M3 Lee]] tanks and participated in the [[Battle of Ramree Island]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Whiting |first1=Charles |last2=Taylor |first2=Eric |date=2008 |title=The Fighting Tykes: An Informal History of the Yorkshire Regiments in the Second World War |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9kt-AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA132 |publisher=Pen & Sword Military |page=132 |isbn=978-1844156450}}</ref> He was promoted to war-substantive [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] on 1&nbsp;October 1942 and to temporary [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 11&nbsp;October 1944.<ref>{{cite book |date=1946 |title=The Quarterly Army List (August 1946 \u2013 Part I) |location=London |publisher=HM Stationery Office |isbn= |pages=385a |url=https://archive.org/details/armylistaugpart121946grea/page/398/mode/2up|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe served in [[Arakan]] in western Burma and afterward in [[Sumatra]] after the [[Surrender of Japan|Japanese surrender]],<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52278746|title=Army veteran, 99, raises \u00a34m for 'humbled' NHS|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref> by which time he had risen to the rank of captain.<ref name=\"Nicholls\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/> On his return to Britain he served as an instructor at the Armoured Fighting Vehicle School in [[Bovington Camp|Bovington]], Dorset.<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/>\n\n=== Decorations ===\n\nFor his war service, Moore was awarded three medals:<ref name=\"ES\">{{cite news |title=War veteran, 99, hits \u00a314m for NHS as Hancock calls him an inspiration |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/war-veteran-tom-moore-matt-hancock-9-million-nhs-a4415496.html |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n*[[1939\u20131945 Star]]\n*[[Burma Star]]\n*[[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]\n\n== Later work and hobbies ==\n\nAfter leaving the army, he worked as managing director of a company manufacturing [[concrete]].<ref name=\"Spary\" />\n\nFor 64 years he organised the DWR's annual reunion.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\nMoore raced motorcycles competitively, wearing the number 23.<ref name=\"Hancocks\">{{cite web |last1=Hancocks |first1=Simon |title=Veteran NHS fundraiser Captain Tom Moore was also a motorcycle racer |url=https://www.visordown.com/news/general/veteran-nhs-fundraiser-captain-tom-moore-was-also-motorcycle-racer |website=Visordown |accessdate=17 April 2020 }}</ref> He rode a [[The Scott Motorcycle Company|Scott motorcycle]], winning several trophies.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\n== Tom's 100th Birthday Walk  ==\n[[File:Captain Tom Moore fundraising walk.jpg|thumb|upright|Moore during the fund-raising initiative walk. He is wearing the [[1939\u20131945 Star]], [[Burma Star]], and [[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]. |alt=Moore wearing a blazer with regimental badge, regimental tie and three medals]]\n\nOn 6 April 2020 he began a fundraising campaign to raise money for [[NHS Charities Together]], a group of charities supporting staff and volunteers caring for COVID-19 patients in the British public health services during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] by aiming to complete one hundred {{convert|25|m|yard|abbr=on}} laps of his garden, ten laps per day, with the help of a [[Walker (mobility)|walking frame]], branding the endeavour \"'''Tom's 100th Birthday Walk For The NHS'''\".<ref name=\"Spary\" /><ref name=\"Low\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52290976\">{{cite web |title=Army veteran's \u00a37m for NHS 'out of this world' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52290976 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe initial \u00a31,000 goal having been realised on Friday 10 April, the target was increased, first to \u00a35,000, and eventually to \u00a3500,000 as more people around the world became involved.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/nhs-100-birthday-walk-army-veteran-tom-moore-fundraise-a9463561.html |title=99-year-old army veteran raises more than \u00a31m for NHS with \u2018100th birthday walk\u2019 |date=14 April 2020 |work=The Independent |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> The fund-raising soared exponentially when the British media publicised the endeavour. Moore, who joined [[Twitter]] in the same month, used the site to express joy over accumulating such a staggering amount of money for the NHS.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=CaptainTomMoore |number=1250418629218168833 |date=15 April 2020 |title=7 MILLION POUNDS!!!! The Great British public, your generosity is just incredible! THANK YOU!! }}</ref> \n\nThe [[JustGiving]] page for his walk reports that, as of 19:00 19 April 2020 (UTC), he had raised in excess of \u00a326.2<!-- please update the figure in two places and the date/ timestamp-->&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"JGTM\">{{cite web |title=Captain Tom Moore's 100th Birthday Walk for the NHS |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs |publisher=[[JustGiving]] |accessdate=19 April 2020 }}</ref> the largest-ever amount raised by a JustGiving campaign,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792|title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |website=inews.co.uk| access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-18098819|title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard|last=Shaw|first=Neil|date=2020-04-16|website=walesonline|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> beating the previous record of \u00a35.2&nbsp;million raised (partially posthumously) by [[Stephen Sutton]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Stephen's fundraising page |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/stephen-sutton-tct |website=JustGiving |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Butterworth\">{{cite news |last1=Butterworth |first1=Benjamin |title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=inews.co.uk }}</ref> More than 1.2 million individuals have donated.<ref name=\"JGTM\" />\n\nFunds raised by Moore are being spent on such things as well-being packs for National Health Service staff facilitating rest and recuperation rooms, devices to enable hospital patients to keep in contact with family members, and community groups who support patients once discharged from hospitals.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52325713\">{{cite web |last1=Shepka |first1=Phil |last2=Lewis |first2=Katy |title=How will Captain Tom Moore's millions be spent? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52325713 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=18 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe achieved his initial target of one hundred laps on the morning of 16 April, watched [[Social distancing measures related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|at a safe distance]] by a [[guard of honour]] from the [[1st Battalion, The Yorkshire Regiment|1st Battalion of the Yorkshire Regiment]],<ref name=\"Shaw\">{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Neil |title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard |url=https://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-4050824 |work=hulldailymail |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> into which the DWR were merged in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx |title=The Yorkshire Regiment |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence]] |archivedate=27 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527064813/http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx }}</ref> He has said he will not stop, and aims to do a second hundred.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" />\n\nOn reaching the \u00a35&nbsp;million mark, Moore explained his motivation:<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-52296313/coronavirus-army-veteran-tom-moore-finds-out-he-s-raised-5m-for-nhs |title=Army veteran, 99, finds out he's raised \u00a35m for NHS |publisher=BBC News |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|When we started off with this exercise we didn't anticipate we'd get anything near that sort of money. It's really amazing. All of them, from top to bottom, in the National Health Service, they deserve everything that we can possibly put in their place. They're all so brave. Because every morning or every night they're putting themselves into harm's way, and I think you've got to give them full marks for that effort. We're a little bit like having a war at the moment. But the doctors and the nurses, they're all on the front line, and all of us behind, we've got to supply them and keep them going with everything that they need, so that they can do their jobs even better than they're doing now.}}\n\n=== Charity recording ===\n\nTo mark Moore's 100th lap, the singer [[Michael Ball]] has recorded a version of \"[[You'll Never Walk Alone]]\", with the NHS Voices of Care Choir, and featuring Moore's spoken words.<ref name=\"ITV\">{{cite news |title=Captain Tom Moore launches You'll Never Walk Alone charity single with Michael Ball |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-18/captain-tom-moore-launches-you-ll-never-walk-alone-charity-single-with-michael-ball/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=ITV News }}</ref> The recording has been released as a digital single by Decca Records.<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web |title=You'll Never Walk Alone - Single by Michael Ball, Captain Tom Moore & The NHS Voices of Care Choir |url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/youll-never-walk-alone/1508494673?i=1508494683&uo=2 |publisher=Apple Music |accessdate=19 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n=== Recognition ===\n\nMoore has given well over 50 media interviews.<ref name=\"BBC-52333127\">{{cite web |title=Capt Tom 'speechless' as fundraising passes \u00a323m |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52333127 |website=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, after Moore's 100th lap, a UK Government spokesman said:<ref name=\"Lovett\">{{cite news |last1=Lovett |first1=Samuel |title=UK death toll rises again as lockdown to be extended \u2013 follow live |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-news-live-update-latest-today-cases-deaths-lockdown-covid-19-a9467756.html#post-1187989853 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The Prime Minister will certainly be looking at ways to recognise Tom's heroic efforts.}}\n\nBy mid-day on 17 April, more than 505,000 people had signed a petition calling for him to be knighted.<ref name=\"BBC-52321262\">{{cite news |title=Prince William hails veteran's \u00a318m NHS fundraiser |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52321262 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBrigadier Andrew Jackson, colonel of the Yorkshire Regiment, described Moore as:<ref name=\"BBC-52340554\">{{cite web |title=Capt Tom to be guest of honour at hospital opening |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-52340554 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|an absolute legend [from] an exceptional generation that are still an inspiration for our Yorkshire soldiers today.}}\n\nKeighley Town Council stated that they grant Moore the [[Freedom of the City|Freedom of Keighley]].<ref name=\"ITV-freedom\">{{cite web |title=Veteran Capt Tom Moore to be given freedom of Keighley after raising \u00a313m for NHS |url=https://www.itv.com/news/calendar/2020-04-16/veteran-capt-tom-moore-to-be-given-freedom-of-keighley-after-raising-13m-for-nhs/ |publisher=ITV News |accessdate=19 April 2020 }}</ref> Moore has also been invited to be guest of honour, via a video link, when [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Yorkshire and the Humber]], in [[Harrogate]], is formally opened on 21 April.<ref name=\"BBC-52340554\" />\n\n===Similar fundraising efforts===\nMoore's success inspired retired Welsh farmer Rhythwyn Evans to launch his own fundraising campaign<ref name=\"JGDE\">{{cite web|title=Her 91 dros COVID-19 Rhythwyn|url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/david-evans186|quote=91st birthday challenge to support local NHS staff for Hywel Dda Health Charities because of their hard work during COVID-19|publisher=Just Giving|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> by walking 91 laps of his bungalow in [[Silian, Ceredigion|Silian]], [[Ceredigion]], on his 91st birthday on 18 April 2020. Evans said that his walk was \"inspired by and in solidarity with Captain Tom Moore\" and that he aimed to raise \u00a31,000 for his local health board \"to give something back to the community\", having lived to a \"ripe old age\". Evans completed the laps before 17:30 and quipped that his next aim was to get \"a good night's sleep!\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/18/welsh-farmer-doing-91-laps-of-bungalow-on-91st-birthday-for-nhs-coronavirus|title=Welsh farmer doing 91 laps of his bungalow on 91st birthday for NHS|publisher=The Guardian|date=18 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-04-19/farmer-91-walks-91-laps-of-his-home-to-raise-funds-for-the-nhs/|title=Farmer, 91, walks 91 laps of his home to raise funds for the NHS|publisher=ITV News|date=19 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> As of 16:00 on 19 April 2020 (UTC), Evans has raised over \u00a329,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/uk-news/2020/04/18/grandfather-walks-91-laps-around-bungalow-on-91st-birthday-to-raise-cash-for-nhs/ |title=Grandfather walks 91 laps around bungalow on 91st birthday to raise cash for NHS|publisher=Shropshire Star|date=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-wales-52333077/coronavirus-capt-tom-moore-inspires-91-year-old-s-walk-for-nhs|title=Coronavirus: Capt Tom Moore inspires 91-year-old's walk for NHS |publisher=BBC News |date=17 April 2020 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMoore married Pamela in 1968,<ref name=\"Lavender\">{{cite news |last1=Lavender |first1=Jane |title=Captain Tom Moore had 'given up on love' before he met beloved late wife aged 50 |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-given-up-21876074 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=mirror |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> and they had two daughters.<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> Pamela died circa 2006.<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> He has lived with one of his daughters, Hannah, her husband, and two grandchildren, in [[Marston Moretaine]], [[Bedfordshire]] since 2008.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /> He also has two other grandchildren.<ref name=\"Brown\" /> In recent years he has received treatment from the NHS for skin cancer and, in 2018, a broken hip.<ref name=\"Brown\" /><ref name=\"Low\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/captain-tom-moore-99-walks-to-raise-millions-for-the-nhs-fzpn0cjfb|title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, raises \u00a35m for NHS with 100th birthday walk|first=Valentine|last=Low|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/99-year-old-army-veteran-raises-2-million-charity-walking-his-backyard-1497742|title=99-year-old army veteran raises $2 million for charity by walking in his backyard|first=Khaleda | last=Rahman|date=14 April 2020|website=Newsweek|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spary\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/14/world/war-veteran-raises-millions-garden-scli-intl-gbr/index.html|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36 million by walking laps of his garden|first=Sara |last=Spary|website=CNN|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs Moore's fund-raising page]\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{YouTube|wUP-ty-Tj5E|You'll Never Walk Alone}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52316856 Captain Tom Moore: How the war veteran captured our hearts] \u2013 BBC news\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Tom}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Charity events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Duke of Wellington's Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:English civil engineers]]\n[[Category:People from Keighley]]\n[[Category:Skin cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Royal Armoured Corps officers]]\n[[Category:English motorcycle racers]]\n", "name_user": "ShastaSHASTA", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRecognition:midday does not need a hyphen", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Moore_(fundraiser)"}
{"title_page": "Room (2015 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2015 British-American-Canadian-Irish drama film by Lenny Abrahamson}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name     = Room\n| image    = Room (2015 film).png\n| alt      =\n| caption  = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Lenny Abrahamson]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ed Guiney]]\n* [[David Gross (producer)|David Gross]]\n}}\n| screenplay = [[Emma Donoghue]]\n| based on   = {{based on |[[Room (novel)|Room]]||Emma Donoghue}}\n| starring   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Brie Larson]]\n* [[Jacob Tremblay]]\n* [[Joan Allen]]\n* [[Sean Bridgers]]\n* [[William H. Macy]]\n}}\n| music                = [[Stephen Rennicks]]\n| cinematography       = [[Danny Cohen (cinematographer)|Danny Cohen]]\n| editing              = [[Nathan Nugent]]\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Filmnation Entertainment]]\n* [[Telefilm Canada]]\n* [[Film4 Productions|Film4]]\n* [[Irish Film Board|B\u00f3rd Scann\u00e1n na h\u00c9ireann/Irish Film Board]]\n* Ontario Media Development Corporation\n* [[Element Pictures]]\n* [[No Trace Camping]]\n* Duperele Films\n}}\n| distributor = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Elevation Pictures]] <small>(Canada)</small>\n* [[StudioCanal UK|StudioCanal]] <small>(United Kingdom and Ireland)</small>\n* [[A24 (company)|A24]] <small>(United States)</small>\n}}\n| released    = {{Film date|2015|09|04|[[Telluride Film Festival|Telluride]]|2015|10|16|United States|2015|10|23|Canada|2016|1|15|United Kingdom and Ireland}}\n| runtime     = 118 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 117:39. This rounds to 118 minutes.--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/room-film | title=''ROOM'' | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 5, 2015 | accessdate=November 5, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151224201317/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/room-film | archive-date=December 24, 2015 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| country     = {{Plainlist|\n* Canada\n* Ireland<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/canada-ireland-oscars-brooklyn-room-1.3467850|title=Canada, Ireland lay claim to Oscar nominees Room and Brooklyn|work=[[CBC News]]|date=27 February 2016|accessdate=July 7, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303014859/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/canada-ireland-oscars-brooklyn-room-1.3467850 |archivedate=March 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ifi.ie/room |title=Room |last=Coyne |first=Kevin |accessdate=23 July 2016 |work=[[Irish Film Institute]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817174859/http://www.ifi.ie/room |archive-date=August 17, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/tiff-2015-room-peoples-choice-award-1.3236653 |title=TIFF 2015: Room wins People's Choice Award as festival wraps |last=The Canadian Press |first= |date=September 21, 2015 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[CBC News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509111926/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/tiff-2015-room-peoples-choice-award-1.3236653 |archivedate=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n* United Kingdom\n* United States<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/56427bb42a08b|title=Room BFI website|work=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=1 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001224405/http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/56427bb42a08b|archive-date=October 1, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n| language = English\n| budget   = $13 million<ref name=\"Whipp\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-en-indie-financing-20151229-story.html|title=With indie films such as 'Brooklyn' and 'Room', the creativity often begins with the financing|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 29, 2015|accessdate=February 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712114927/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-en-indie-financing-20151229-story.html|archive-date=July 12, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| gross    = $36.3 million<ref name=\"The Numbers\">{{cite web |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Room-(2015)#tab=summary |title=Room (2016) |website=The Numbers |accessdate=March 28, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405153826/http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Room-(2015)#tab=summary#tab=summary |archive-date=April 5, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Room''''' is a 2015 [[independent film|independent]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Lenny Abrahamson]] and written by [[Emma Donoghue]], based on her [[Room (novel)|2010 novel of the same name]]. It stars [[Brie Larson]] as a woman who has been held captive for seven years and whose 5-year-old son ([[Jacob Tremblay]]) was born in captivity. Their escape allows the boy to experience the outside world for the first time. The film also stars [[Joan Allen]], [[Sean Bridgers]], and [[William H. Macy]].\n\nThe film was a co-production of Canada, Ireland, the United Kingdom, and the United States and was shot in [[Toronto]], with the eponymous set built at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]]. The crew designed each part of the set for the room to be removable to provide access for the crew. Larson researched trauma and nutrition for her part.\n\n''Room'' premiered at the [[Telluride Film Festival]] on September 4, 2015, and later screened at the [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]], where it received the People's Choice Award. The film was theatrically released in Canada on October 23, 2015 by [[Elevation Pictures]] and in the United Kingdom and Ireland on January 15, 2016 by [[StudioCanal UK|StudioCanal]]. It began a [[limited release|limited theatrical run]] in the United States on October 16, 2015 by [[A24 (company)|A24]]. ''Room'' received critical acclaim for Larson's and Tremblay's performances and the storytelling, and grossed $36.3 million on a $13 million budget.\n\nCited as one of the best films of the year, [[List of accolades received by Room|''Room'' received numerous awards and nominations]]. At the [[88th Academy Awards]], ''Room'' received four nominations, including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], and winning [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for Larson. It also won nine [[4th Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Awards]], including [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Motion Picture|Best Motion Picture]], and seven [[13th Irish Film & Television Awards|Irish Film & Television Awards]], including Best Film. Larson won the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] for Best Actress.\n\n==Plot==\nIn [[Akron, Ohio]], 24-year-old Joy Newsome and her 5-year-old son Jack live in a squalid shed they call Room. They share a bed, toilet, bathtub, television, and rudimentary kitchen; the only window is a skylight. They are captives of a man they call \"Old Nick\", Jack's biological father, who abducted Joy seven years prior and routinely rapes her while Jack sleeps in the closet. She tries to stay optimistic for her son but suffers from malnutrition and depression. She allows Jack to believe that only Room and its contents are real, and that the rest of the world exists only on television.\n\nOld Nick tells Joy that he has lost his job and threatens that he may not be able to afford their supplies in the future. That night, Jack is overcome with curiosity and ventures out of the closet while Old Nick is asleep in bed with his mother. Joy is horrified when she awakens and sees their interaction, slapping Old Nick away. As punishment, he cuts their heat and power. Joy decides to tell Jack about the outside world; he reacts with disbelief and incomprehension, but also curiosity. She has Jack fake a fever, hoping that Old Nick will take him to a hospital where he can alert the authorities, but Old Nick says he will return the following day with antibiotics.\n\nJoy wraps Jack in a carpet and has him play dead in the hope that Old Nick will remove him from Room. Falling for the ruse, Old Nick places Jack in the back of his pickup truck and drives through a residential neighborhood. Although stunned by his first exposure to the outside world, Jack jumps from the truck and attracts the attention of a passerby. The police arrive and rescue him. The police discover Joy as well, and take her and Jack to a hospital. Old Nick is captured and arrested.\n\nReunited with her family, Joy learns that her parents have divorced and that her mother has a new partner, Leo. She returns with Jack to her childhood home where her mother and Leo reside. Her father cannot accept Jack as his grandchild and leaves. Jack struggles to adjust to life in the larger world, speaking only to his mother and expressing a desire to return to Room. Joy struggles with anger and depression, lashing out at her mother and becoming worried about Jack's lack of interaction with \"real\" things. At the suggestion of the family's lawyer, Joy agrees to a television interview, but becomes upset when the interviewer questions her decision to keep the newborn Jack instead of asking Old Nick to take him to a hospital. Overwhelmed with guilt, she attempts suicide; Jack finds her unconscious in the bathroom, and she is admitted to a hospital.\n\nJack misses his mother but begins to settle into his new life. He bonds with his new family, meets Leo's dog, Seamus, and makes friends with a boy his age. Believing his long hair will give Joy the strength she needs to recover, Jack has his grandmother cut it for him so he can send it to her. Joy returns home and apologizes, thanking Jack for saving her life again. At Jack's request, they visit Room one last time, escorted by police. Jack is confused; he feels it has shrunk and that it is a different place with the door open. He and Joy say their goodbyes to Room and leave.\n\n==Cast==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Brie Larson]] as Joy \"Ma\" Newsome\n* [[Jacob Tremblay]] as Jack Newsome\n* [[Joan Allen]] as Nancy Newsome\n* [[William H. Macy]] as Robert Newsome\n* [[Sean Bridgers]] as Old Nick\n* [[Tom McCamus]] as Leo\n* [[Amanda Brugel]] as Officer Parker\n* [[Joe Pingue]] as Officer Tom Grabowski\n* [[Cas Anvar]] as Dr. Mittal\n* [[Wendy Crewson]] as Talk Show Hostess\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[File:Irish-Canadian author Emma Donoghue.JPG|upright|thumb|Irish-Canadian author [[Emma Donoghue]] adapted her novel ''[[Room (novel)|Room]]'', served as [[executive producer]] for the film and supported [[Lenny Abrahamson]]'s bid to direct]]\n[[Emma Donoghue]], who also wrote the [[Room (novel)|novel on which the film is based]], wrote the screenplay for the film before the novel was published in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/emma-donoghue-oscars-1.3466881 |title=Oscar-nominated Emma Donoghue wrote Room screenplay before book came out |last=Nathoo |first=Zulekha |date=February 26, 2016 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[CBC News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612105758/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/emma-donoghue-oscars-1.3466881 |archivedate=June 12, 2016 }}</ref> She explained she felt sure the book could be made into a film because of its structured storyline, and received many offers from filmmakers after it was published, which she rejected for creative reasons.<ref name=\"Medley\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/on-set-of-the-room-as-donoghue-watches-her-novel-come-to-filmic-life/article26930003/ |title=On set of the Room as Donoghue watches her novel come to filmic life |last=Medley |first=Mark |date=22 October 2015 |accessdate=26 July 2016 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219195939/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/on-set-of-the-room-as-donoghue-watches-her-novel-come-to-filmic-life/article26930003/ |archive-date=December 19, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Director [[Lenny Abrahamson]] read the novel and sent Donoghue a 10-page [[fan mail|fan letter]] telling her it should be a film, without knowing a screenplay already existed. Donoghue felt the letter demonstrated an understanding of her work and advocated for him as director.<ref name=\"Fear\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/room-how-a-dark-indie-became-2015s-left-field-oscar-contender-20151112 |title='Room': How a Dark Indie Became 2015's Left-Field Oscar Contender |last=Fear |first=David |date=November 12, 2015 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831185410/http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/room-how-a-dark-indie-became-2015s-left-field-oscar-contender-20151112 |archive-date=August 31, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Abrahamson and Donoghue spent one week at her house in [[London, Ontario]] as they revised the screenplay.<ref name=\"Medley\"/> She served as [[executive producer]] and was included in major filmmaking decisions.<ref name=\"Earlyedition\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/emma-donoghue-author-of-bestseller-room-talks-about-turning-her-book-into-a-film-1.3247359 |title=Emma Donoghue, author of bestseller Room, talks about turning her book into a film |last=The Early Edition |date=September 28, 2015 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814154007/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/emma-donoghue-author-of-bestseller-room-talks-about-turning-her-book-into-a-film-1.3247359 |archive-date=August 14, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Abrahamson credited Donoghue with securing funding from Canada, where she is a citizen.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/markets-festivals/room-brie-larson-lenny-abrahamson-toronto-jacob-tremblay1201619031-1201619031/ |title='Room' Director Abrahamson Makes Unlikely Stories Accessible |last=Wise |first=Damon |date=15 October 2015 |accessdate=23 July 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170624090711/http://variety.com/2015/film/markets-festivals/room-brie-larson-lenny-abrahamson-toronto-jacob-tremblay1201619031-1201619031/ |archive-date=June 24, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> She also suggested shooting in [[Toronto]] because it could resemble the United States, and she believed it would be awkward for many Irish filmmakers to work in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/artsfilmtv/emma-donoghue-on-the-room-with-a-different-view-356519.html |title=Emma Donoghue on the Room with a different view |last=Barlow |first=Helen |date=30 September 2015 |accessdate=23 July 2016 |work=[[Irish Examiner]]}}</ref> Canadian producer [[David Gross (producer)|David Gross]] helped persuade his Irish co-producers to shoot in Canada rather than the U.S., saying they could have a longer schedule and more money in Canada.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tiff-2015-why-canadian-productions-822452 |title=TIFF: Why Canadian Co-Productions Thrive in Ontario |last=Vlessing |first=Etan |date=12 September 2015 |accessdate=23 January 2017 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202031512/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tiff-2015-why-canadian-productions-822452 |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:Jacob Tremblay (22859198313) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Canadian child actor [[Jacob Tremblay]] was chosen from dozens of young performers for the part of Jack, and went on to win the [[4th Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Award]] for [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.torontosun.com/2016/03/19/rooms-jacob-tremblay-shows-young-stars-have-come-a-long-way |title=Room's Jacob Tremblay shows young stars have come a long way |last=Slotek |first=Jim |date=19 March 2016 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[Toronto Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916160202/http://www.torontosun.com/2016/03/19/rooms-jacob-tremblay-shows-young-stars-have-come-a-long-way |archive-date=September 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>]]\n[[Emma Watson]], [[Rooney Mara]], [[Shailene Woodley]] and [[Mia Wasikowska]] were considered for the role of Joy.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/brie-larsons-20-year-climb-857011 |title=Brie Larson's 20-Year Climb to Overnight Stardom: I'm 'Totally Out of My Comfort Zone' |last=Sandell |first=Laurie |date=20 January 2016 |accessdate=23 July 2016 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802034854/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/brie-larsons-20-year-climb-857011 |archive-date=August 2, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Brie Larson]] was cast after an associate of Abrahamson suggested he see her in ''[[Short Term 12]]''.<ref name=\"Fear\" /> Larson consulted with a trauma expert and nutritionist for the role,<ref name=\"Harrowing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/brie-larson-why-room-more-lovely-harrowing-226628|title=Brie Larson on why Room is more \"lovely\" than \"harrowing\"|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last1=Bramesco|first1=Charles|accessdate=14 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016023639/http://www.avclub.com/article/brie-larson-why-room-more-lovely-harrowing-226628|archive-date=October 16, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> went on a restrictive diet, and avoided sunlight.<ref name=\"Ahearn\"/> She said she saw the film less as a crime story and more of \"a story of love and freedom and perseverance and what it feels like to grow up and become your own person\".<ref name=\"Harrowing\" />\n\nThe filmmakers considered dozens of child actors for Jack before choosing seven-year-old [[Jacob Tremblay]] from [[Vancouver]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/room-builds-buzz-awards-1.3285386 |title=Room, starring Brie Larson and Jacob Tremblay, earns Oscar buzz despite dark subject matter |last=Sumanac-Johnson |first=Deana |date=October 23, 2015 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[CBC News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320051119/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/room-builds-buzz-awards-1.3285386 |archivedate=20 March 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"Ahearn\"/> Tremblay said his part was not hard \"because I was playing a happy child\" unaware of the sinister nature of Room.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/in-contention/room-brie-larson-praises-jacob-tremblay-1201652086/ |title='Room's' Brie Larson, Joan Allen Praise Breakout Star Jacob Tremblay (Video) |last=Riley |first=Jenelle |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205184412/https://variety.com/2015/film/in-contention/room-brie-larson-praises-jacob-tremblay-1201652086/ |archive-date=February 5, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> As he was too young to read the whole screenplay, each scene was explained to him one by one.<ref name=\"Ahearn\"/> Tremblay wore a [[wig]] made from human hair.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/144256-did-jacob-tremblay-wear-a-wig-in-room-that-long-hair-was-very-convincing |title=Did Jacob Tremblay Wear A Wig In 'Room'? That Long Hair Was Very Convincing |last=McGahan |first=Michelle |date=February 25, 2016 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708075302/http://www.bustle.com/articles/144256-did-jacob-tremblay-wear-a-wig-in-room-that-long-hair-was-very-convincing |archive-date=July 8, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> According to [[Joan Allen]], who played Nancy, Larson and Tremblay met for over three weeks to build a \"very tight, obviously critical, close relationship\", before the Room scenes were shot over five weeks. Allen arrived in Toronto later and met Tremblay, \"But we didn't want him to become too familiar with me because that's not what the story is.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/joan-allen-on-room/ |title=Joan Allen on 'Room' |last=Freshwater |first=Lori |date=December 20, 2015 |accessdate=July 23, 2016 |work=[[Los Angeles Review of Books]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812113129/https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/joan-allen-on-room/ |archive-date=August 12, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn preparing for her own role, Allen did not consult real mothers of kidnapped children, but said she reflected on her own experiences \"in a mall when my daughter was little and I look around and within a flash she's not there\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://parade.com/459480/walterscott/did-joan-allen-do-research-for-her-role-in-room/ |title=Did Joan Allen Do Research for her Role in Room? |last=Scott |first=Walter |date=26 February 2016 |accessdate=29 July 2016 |work=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817220742/http://parade.com/459480/walterscott/did-joan-allen-do-research-for-her-role-in-room/ |archive-date=August 17, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Canadian actor [[Tom McCamus]] auditioned for the part of Old Nick before being cast as Leo.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-en-mn-small-roles-20151222-story.html |title=Four actors leave big impressions with small roles |date=22 December 2015 |accessdate=29 July 2016 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809200807/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-en-mn-small-roles-20151222-story.html |archive-date=August 9, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The actors improvised some lines, with Donoghue saying they created \"speech patterns more natural-sounding than I could have written, and produced some brilliant new lines that ended up in the film.\"<ref name=\"Earlyedition\" />\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:TorontoPinewoodStudios.JPG|thumb|The only ''Room'' set was built at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]] by production designer [[Ethan Tobman]]]]\nAbrahamson used only one Room set, wanting to create an authentic experience for Tremblay.<ref name=\"Tapley\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/in-contention/room-set-10-feet-production-designer-cinematographer-1201643947/ |title='Room': Creating a Whole World in a 10-Foot Space |last=Tapley |first=Kristopher |date=19 November 2015 |accessdate=27 July 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205184837/https://variety.com/2015/film/in-contention/room-set-10-feet-production-designer-cinematographer-1201643947/ |archive-date=February 5, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The set, built on a soundstage at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]],<ref name=\"Tapley\"/> was {{convert|11|\u00d7|11|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Buxton\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/lenny-abrahamson-room-bathtub_us_56743d34e4b014efe0d53b72 |title=Why 'Room' Director Lenny Abrahamson Spent A Month Hiding In A Bathtub |last=Buxton |first=Ryan |date=December 18, 2015 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802192250/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/lenny-abrahamson-room-bathtub_us_56743d34e4b014efe0d53b72 |archive-date=August 2, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Montreal]] production designer [[Ethan Tobman]] set out with the idea \"that every square inch of Room needed to have a backstory\".<ref name=\"Brunhuber\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/room-set-design-trauma-1.3460087 |title=Oscar-nominated Room required painstaking precision from cast and crew |last=Brunhuber |first=Kim |date=February 25, 2016 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[CBC News]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612172620/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/room-set-design-trauma-1.3460087 |archivedate=12 June 2016}}</ref> To fit the crew and equipment into the small space, he made each piece of the set removable. However, as Abrahamson and cinematographer [[Danny Cohen (cinematographer)|Danny Cohen]] wanted the camera to always shoot scenes from inside Room, the lens was always positioned within the set even if the rest of the camera was outside.<ref name=\"Brunhuber\" /> There were as many as eight cameramen at a time inside the Room set with Larson and Tremblay.<ref name=\"Ahearn\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.news1130.com/2015/10/21/brie-larson-on-room-role-bonding-with-clever-young-co-star-jacob-tremblay/ |title=Brie Larson on 'Room' role, bonding with clever young co-star Jacob Tremblay |last=Ahearn |first=Victoria |date=October 21, 2015 |accessdate=March 17, 2017 |publisher=[[The Canadian Press]] |work=[[CKWX]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318023312/http://www.news1130.com/2015/10/21/brie-larson-on-room-role-bonding-with-clever-young-co-star-jacob-tremblay/ |archive-date=March 18, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The actors also made the [[Theatrical property|props]] decorating the set.<ref name=\"Tapley\"/>\n\nBecause the scenes set outside Room were filmed after the scenes inside, the crew was initially eager to leave the cramped space, expecting that the rest of the film would be easy.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.avclub.com/article/brie-larson-why-room-more-lovely-harrowing-226628 |title=Brie Larson on why Room is more 'lovely' than 'harrowing' |last=Bramesco |first=Charles |date=14 October 2015 |accessdate=27 July 2016 |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016023639/http://www.avclub.com/article/brie-larson-why-room-more-lovely-harrowing-226628 |archive-date=October 16, 2015 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> However, they had difficulty adjusting to the cold weather, traffic and crowds in Toronto.<ref name=\"Buxton\" /> Cohen remarked that upon returning to the Room set for the final scene, the set appeared smaller to the crew.<ref name=\"Lytal\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-en-danny-cohen-danish-girl-20151203-story.html |title=The cinematographer of 'The Danish Girl' and 'Room' details shooting such 'extreme opposites' |last=Lytal |first=Cristy |date=3 December 2015 |accessdate=27 July 2016 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817051052/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-en-danny-cohen-danish-girl-20151203-story.html |archive-date=August 17, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nCohen used a [[Panavision cameras|Panavision Primos]] lens on a [[Red Digital Cinema|Red Epic Dragon]] camera, saying \"The Primos and using Kino Flos, which is more akin to fluorescent lighting, gave ''Room'' a certain texture, a certain look.\"<ref name=\"Lytal\"/> [[Principal photography]] began on 10 November 2014<ref name=\"Filming\">{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=AFM: William H. Macy, Joan Allen Join Brie Larson's 'Room'|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/afm-william-h-macy-joan-allen-join-brie-larsons-room-1201352555/|accessdate=17 November 2014|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=10 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206002532/https://variety.com/2014/film/news/afm-william-h-macy-joan-allen-join-brie-larsons-room-1201352555/|archive-date=February 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and ended on 15 December 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=On The Set for 12/15/14: JJ Abrams Wraps 'The Cellar', Tom Hiddleston Finishes 'I Saw the Light' & More|url=http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-121514-jj-abrams-wraps-the-cellar-tom-hiddleston-finishes-i-saw-the-light-more/|accessdate=16 December 2014|website=ssninsider.com|date=15 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924105339/http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-121514-jj-abrams-wraps-the-cellar-tom-hiddleston-finishes-i-saw-the-light-more/|archivedate=September 24, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\nEditor [[Nathan Nugent]] served as second-unit director.<ref name=\"Murphy\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/23/movies/below-the-line-editing-room.html?_r=0 |title=Below the Line: Editing 'Room' |last=Murphy |first=Mekado |date=23 December 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2017 |work=[[The New York Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103133855/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/23/movies/below-the-line-editing-room.html?_r=0 |archive-date=January 3, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He described his editing of ''Room'' as simplistic, keeping the acting intact, while working in [[Dublin]] for five months.<ref name=\"Grobar\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/nathan-nugent-editor-room-interview-oscars-2015-1201653335/ |title=Editor Nathan Nugent On 'Room': 'We Tried Not To Get In The Way Of The Great Performances' |last=Grobar |first=Matt |date=7 December 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2017 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621143548/https://deadline.com/2015/12/nathan-nugent-editor-room-interview-oscars-2015-1201653335/ |archive-date=June 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> However, Tremblay's part was filmed in numerous takes so Tremblay could give variations of his performances of specific lines, so Abrahamson and Nugent had to assemble and splice the different takes in the editing process.<ref name=\"Murphy\"/>\n\n==Release==\nPrior to production, [[A24 (company)|A24]] acquired U.S. distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ford|first1=Rebecca|title=Cannes: Brie Larson Drama 'Room' Goes to A24 Films|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-brie-larson-drama-room-705279|accessdate=17 November 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=18 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116224402/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-brie-larson-drama-room-705279|archive-date=January 16, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''Room'' had its world premiere on September 4, 2015, at the [[Telluride Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elementpictures.ie/news/lenny-abrahamsons-room-to-have-world-premiere-at-the-telluride-film-festival/|title=Lenny Abrahamson's ''Room'' to have world premiere at the Telluride Film Festival|website=Elementpictures.ie|date=September 4, 2015|accessdate=February 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304200053/http://elementpictures.ie/news/lenny-abrahamsons-room-to-have-world-premiere-at-the-telluride-film-festival/|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It went on to screen in the Special Presentations section at the [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"ScreenDaily\">{{cite web|url = http://www.screendaily.com/toronto-world-premieres-for-trumbo-demolition-the-program/5090990.article?blocktitle=LATEST-FILM-NEWS&contentID=40562#|title = Toronto to open with 'Demolition'; world premieres for 'Trumbo', 'The Program'|date = 28 July 2015|accessdate = 28 July 2015|work = [[Screen Daily]]|archive-url = https://archive.is/20150729193951/http://www.screendaily.com/toronto-world-premieres-for-trumbo-demolition-the-program/5090990.article?blocktitle=LATEST-FILM-NEWS&contentID=40562%23|archive-date = July 29, 2015|url-status = live|df = mdy-all}}</ref> and at the [[BFI London Film Festival|London Film Festival]], on October 11, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whatson.bfi.org.uk/lff/Online/default.asp?BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::permalink=room|title=Room|website=[[BFI London Film Festival]]|accessdate=February 13, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311045648/https://whatson.bfi.org.uk/lff/Online/default.asp?BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::permalink=room|archive-date=March 11, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film began a [[limited release]] on October 15, 2015.<ref name=\"Variety1\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/brie-larson-room-october-release-1201552606/ |title=Brie Larson's 'Room' Set for Oct 16 Release |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=29 July 2015 |accessdate=16 September 2015 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205184834/https://variety.com/2015/film/news/brie-larson-room-october-release-1201552606/ |archive-date=February 5, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''Room'' was released in the United Kingdom and Ireland on January 15, 2016, by [[StudioCanal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/a6800516.html |title=Room: Poignant exclusive clip sees Brie Larson make a birthday cake for the most adorable five-year-old |work=[[The Independent]] |first=Jess |last=Denham |date=7 January 2016 |accessdate=18 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930175633/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/a6800516.html |archive-date=September 30, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jan/17/room-review-lenny-abrahamson-brie-larson-jacob-tremblay |title=Room review \u2013 to see the world within four walls |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Mark |last=Kermode |authorlink=Mark Kermode |date=17 January 2016 |accessdate=18 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620014403/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jan/17/room-review-lenny-abrahamson-brie-larson-jacob-tremblay |archive-date=June 20, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/oscar-nominations-room-lenny-abrahamson-ed-guiney-brie-larson-michael-fassbender-emma-stone-olivia-colman-1201683286/ |title=Oscar Nominations: Friendship Is Crucial Element For 'Room's Lenny Abrahamson And Ed Guiney |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |last1=Jaafar |first1=Ali |last2=Fleming |first2=Mike Jr. |date=14 January 2016 |accessdate=18 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318173154/http://deadline.com/2016/01/oscar-nominations-room-lenny-abrahamson-ed-guiney-brie-larson-michael-fassbender-emma-stone-olivia-colman-1201683286/ |archive-date=March 18, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> It went into [[wide release]] on January 22, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/ride-along-2-begins-to-zoom-in-thursday-previews-box-office-1201683644/ |title='Ride Along 2' Continues No. 1 Journey With $41.5M; '13 Hours' Clocks $19.65M \u2013 Monday Update |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=18 January 2016 |accessdate=28 February 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117101525/http://deadline.com/2016/01/ride-along-2-begins-to-zoom-in-thursday-previews-box-office-1201683644/ |archive-date=January 17, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe film was released by [[Lionsgate]] on [[DVD-Video|DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] in the United States on March 1, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/news/a42591/movies-stream-march-2016/ |title=Here Are the Must-Stream Movies of March 2016 |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |last=Schager |first=Nick |date=1 March 2016 |accessdate=18 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319022741/http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/news/a42591/movies-stream-march-2016/ |archive-date=March 19, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> It was released on DVD and Blu-ray in UK and Ireland in May 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irishnews.com/arts/film/2016/05/20/news/dvd-of-the-week-room-524924/ |title=DVD of the week: Room |last=Roy |first=David |date=20 May 2016 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[The Irish News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816142250/http://www.irishnews.com/arts/film/2016/05/20/news/dvd-of-the-week-room-524924/ |archive-date=August 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nAfter its U.S. release on October 16, 2015, ''Room'' played in a peak of 198 theaters from December 11 to 13, and grossed $5,166,724 before its Academy Award nominations were announced, making it one of the lowest-grossing Best Picture nominees in years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/01/room-best-picture-gross-box-office.html |title=Room Was Nominated for Best Picture Despite Making Historically Little Money |last=Lincoln |first=Kevin |date=January 14, 2016 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[Vulture.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819195851/http://www.vulture.com/2016/01/room-best-picture-gross-box-office.html |archive-date=August 19, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Initial box office under-performance came as a surprise to Canada's [[Elevation Pictures]], since winning the People's Choice Award at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] was usually a predictor of financial success.<ref name=\"Houpt\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/the-marketing-quest-to-turn-room-into-a-populist-hit/article28321890/ |title=The marketing quest to turn Room into a populist hit |last=Houpt |first=Simon |date=21 January 2016 |accessdate=26 July 2016 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515081409/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/the-marketing-quest-to-turn-room-into-a-populist-hit/article28321890/ |archive-date=May 15, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> However, the nominations gave the film a boost at the box office, and after opening in the [[Republic of Ireland]] on 15 January, it initially made \u20ac200,000 at 50 theatres.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/technow/movies/room-triumphs-at-the-box-office-376832.html |title=Room triumphs at the box office |last= |first= |date=January 18, 2016 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[Irish Examiner]]}}</ref>\n\nA month after its release in Ireland, it had grossed more than \u20ac1 million nationwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irishfilmboard.ie/irish_film_industry/news/Congratulations_to_the_Irish_Films_BROOKLYN_amp_ROOM_on_Winning_BAFTA_AWARDS/3021 |title=Congratulations to the Irish Films Brooklyn & Room on Winning BAFTA Awards |publisher=[[Irish Film Board]] |accessdate=23 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314222927/http://www.irishfilmboard.ie/irish_film_industry/news/Congratulations_to_the_Irish_Films_BROOKLYN_amp_ROOM_on_Winning_BAFTA_AWARDS/3021 |archive-date=March 14, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On 24 April, ''Room'' completed its run having grossed an estimated $14.7 million in North America and $20.7 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $35.4 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=room2015.htm |title=Room (2016) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=23 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724064437/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=room2015.htm |archive-date=July 24, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> on a $13 million budget.<ref name=\"Whipp\"/>\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{Anchor|Critics|Critical response}}\n[[File:Brie Larson by Gage Skidmore.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Brie Larson]]'s performance as Joy \"Ma\" Newsome received widespread acclaim and earned her the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]]]]\n\n''Room'' received widespread critical acclaim. [[Review aggregator|Review aggregation]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a rating of 93%, based on 303 reviews, with an average rating of 8.46/10. The site's critical consensus states, \"Led by incredible work from Brie Larson and Jacob Tremblay, ''Room'' makes for an unforgettably harrowing\u2014and undeniably rewarding\u2014experience.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/room_2015/ | title=Room (2015) | work=Rotten Tomatoes | publisher=[[Flixster]] | accessdate=3 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423060000/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/room_2015/ | archive-date=April 23, 2016 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gives the film a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 86 out of 100, based on reviews from 43 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/room-2015 | title=Room Reviews | work=Metacritic | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=9 December 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912232938/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/room-2015 | archive-date=September 12, 2015 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Todd McCarthy]] from ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote, \"Overall, it's a decent shot at a tall target, but real credit is due the lead actors, with Larson expanding beyond the already considerable range she's previously shown with an exceedingly dimensional performance in a role that calls for running the gamut, and Tremblay always convincing without ever becoming cloying.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/room-telluride-review-820547|title='Room': Telluride Review|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Todd|last=McCarthy|date=4 September 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212004042/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/room-telluride-review-820547|archive-date=December 12, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Eric Kohn of ''[[IndieWire]]'' stated, \"Brie Larson and newcomer Jacob Tremblay['s]... textured performances turn outrageous circumstances into a tense and surprisingly credible survival tale.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/telluride-review-brie-larson-is-a-revelation-alongside-stunning-newcomer-jacob-tremblay-in-room-20150904|title=Telluride Review: Brie Larson is a Revelation Alongside Stunning Newcomer Jacob Tremblay in 'Room'|work=Indiewire|first=Eric|last=Kohn|date=4 September 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225151502/http://www.indiewire.com/article/telluride-review-brie-larson-is-a-revelation-alongside-stunning-newcomer-jacob-tremblay-in-room-20150904|archive-date=December 25, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' called the film \"the most impressive piece of filmmaking I've seen in 2015, and one of the best movies of the decade\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Room|url=http://roomthemovie.com/#/press|website=Room the Movie (official website) |accessdate=January 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160104091912/http://roomthemovie.com/#/press#/press|archive-date=January 4, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Rex Reed]] said ''Room'' is \"so powerful and unforgettable that it must be seen\" but \"too grim and heartbreaking for some viewers\".<ref name=\"Houpt\"/>\n\nThe central performances of Brie Larson and Jacob Tremblay have received critical acclaim. Joe Morgenstern of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' said \"this drama is as big as all outdoors in scope; poetic and profound in its exploration of the senses; blessed with two transcendent performances, by Brie Larson and Jacob Tremblay; and as elegantly wrought as any film that has come our way in a very long while.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Morgenstern|first1=Joe|title='Room': Downsized Space, Vibrant Life|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/room-downsized-space-vibrant-life-1444933986|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=February 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318173951/https://www.wsj.com/articles/room-downsized-space-vibrant-life-1444933986|archive-date=March 18, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' wrote, \"All you need to know is that the performances of Larson and Tremblay will blow you away. Tremblay is a child actor incapable of a false move. And Larson, so good in ''[[Short Term 12]]'', is magnificent, finding a way into Joy's bruised psyche that tears at your heart.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Travers|first1=Peter|title=Room|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/room-20151015|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=February 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901194824/http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/room-20151015|archive-date=September 1, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe film received positive reviews in its countries of origin, with Barry Hertz of Canada's ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' writing \"''Room'' is a film of tiny little miracles,\" finding it uplifting, praising Larson's performance and referring to Tremblay as \"a wide-eyed wonder who is always genuine\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/film-reviews/room-uplifting-tale-of-miracles-and-love-bound-by-a-horrific-kidnapping/article26936865/ |title=Room: Uplifting tale of miracles and love bound by a horrific kidnapping |last=Hertz |first=Barry |date=October 23, 2015 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126173811/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/film-reviews/room-uplifting-tale-of-miracles-and-love-bound-by-a-horrific-kidnapping/article26936865/ |archive-date=November 26, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Chris Knight for the ''[[National Post]]'' called Tremblay \"preternaturally talented\", and said ''Room'' \"works on a tiny canvas, but in doing so it emphasizes that great things can be accomplished in tight spaces\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/arts/movies/room-review-how-a-single-room-acts-as-an-allegory-for-the-chamber-of-our-own-minds |title=Room review: How a single room acts as an allegory for the chamber of our own minds |last=Knight |first=Chris |date=22 October 2015 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[National Post]] |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20160320175910/http://news.nationalpost.com/arts/movies/room-review-how-a-single-room-acts-as-an-allegory-for-the-chamber-of-our-own-minds |archive-date=March 20, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Liz Braun of the ''[[Toronto Sun]]'' said Jack's narration made the Room scenes \"joyful\" as well as claustrophobic, and that Larson and Tremblay's performances are \"completely engaging\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.torontosun.com/2015/10/22/room-review-film-finds-uplifting-message-in-chilling-tale-of-captivity |title='Room' review: Film finds uplifting message in chilling tale of captivity |last=Braun |first=Liz |date=22 October 2015 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[Toronto Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916154557/http://www.torontosun.com/2015/10/22/room-review-film-finds-uplifting-message-in-chilling-tale-of-captivity |archive-date=September 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Linda Barnard of the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' called ''Room'' \"equally tender and chilling\",<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2015/10/22/drama-room-chilling-yet-uplifting-review.html |title=Drama Room chilling yet uplifting: review |last=Barnard |first=Linda |date=22 October 2015 |accessdate=27 July 2016 |work=[[Toronto Star]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816173612/https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2015/10/22/drama-room-chilling-yet-uplifting-review.html |archive-date=August 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In Ireland, Donald Clarke of ''[[The Irish Times]]'' gave the film five stars, calling it \"harrowing\", and concluded, \"We are left with a film that manages a degree of optimism in the most unpromising circumstances. It is a substantial achievement.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/room-review-home-is-where-the-room-is-1.2496697 |title=Room review: home is where the room is |last=Clarke |first=Donald |date=14 January 2016 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160213091807/http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/room-review-home-is-where-the-room-is-1.2496697 |archive-date=February 13, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Daniel Anderson, writing for the ''[[Irish Examiner]]'', called ''Room'' \"an utterly unique tale which has seen the filmmaker deservedly thrust onto the world stage\", but also \"bleak\" and \"difficult to recommend\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/technow/movies/room-review-375990.html |title=Room review |last=Anderson |first=Daniel |date=13 January 2016 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[Irish Examiner]]}}</ref>\n\nDissenting, [[Kyle Smith]] of the ''[[New York Post]]'' wrote \"The script ... doesn't illuminate what kind of internal damage might be wrought by being held prisoner for seven years: On-screen it simply looks like Joy has a case of the sads.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=In 'Room', Brie Larson tries to win a no-makeup Oscar|url=https://nypost.com/2015/10/14/in-room-brie-larson-tries-to-win-a-no-makeup-oscar/|website=The New York Post|accessdate=13 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201032024/https://nypost.com/2015/10/14/in-room-brie-larson-tries-to-win-a-no-makeup-oscar/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Matthew Lickona of the ''[[San Diego Reader]]'' also called it \"a cowardly movie about brave people\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sandiegoreader.com/movies/room/# |title=Room |last=Lickona |first=Matthew |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[San Diego Reader]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813163206/http://www.sandiegoreader.com/movies/room/ |archive-date=August 13, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{main|List of accolades received by Room}}\n''Room'' has received many awards and nominations. [[Brie Larson]]'s performance in particular has been singled out for awards, with the [[National Board of Review]],<ref name=NBR>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/2015/12/national-board-of-review-announces-2015-award-winners/|title=National Board of Review Announces 2015 Award Winners|website=[[National Board of Review]]|accessdate=July 17, 2016|date=December 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418070538/http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/2015/12/national-board-of-review-announces-2015-award-winners/|archive-date=April 18, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Chicago Film Critics Association|Chicago Film Critics]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Gire|first=Dann|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20151216/entlife/151219073/|title='Mad Max: Fury Road' wins best picture from Chicago Film Critics|work=Daily Herald|date=December 17, 2015|accessdate=December 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218061449/http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20151216/entlife/151219073/|archive-date=December 18, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and various other film critic organizations awarding her Best Actress. Larson has also won several major awards, including the [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Academy Award]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35313266|title=Oscars 2016: Winners list in full|website=[[BBC News]]|date=February 28, 2016|accessdate=February 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225011630/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35313266|archive-date=February 25, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Critics' Choice Movie Awards|Critics' Choice Award]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Rosen|first=Christopher|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/01/17/critics-choice-awards-2016-winners-list|title=Critics' Choice Awards 2016 winners: Spotlight, Mad Max, Leonardo DiCaprio, and more|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=January 17, 2016|accessdate=February 17, 2016|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6ecsPvoj9?url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/01/17/critics-choice-awards-2016-winners-list|archive-date=January 18, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Screen Actors Guild]],<ref name=SAG>{{cite web|url=http://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/22nd-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards|title=The 22nd Annual Screen Actors Guild Awards|website=[[Screen Actors Guild Awards]]|accessdate=February 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024171400/http://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/22nd-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards|archive-date=October 24, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[British Academy Film Awards|BAFTA Award]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35260399|title=Bafta Film Awards 2016: Winners|website=BBC News|date=February 14, 2016|accessdate=May 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160214053026/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35260399|archive-date=February 14, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the [[Golden Globe Award]] for Best Actress.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-et-mn-golden-globes-2016-nominees-winners-list-story.html|title=Golden Globes 2016: Complete list of nominees|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=December 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202175445/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-et-mn-golden-globes-2016-nominees-winners-list-story.html|archive-date=December 2, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Emma Donoghue]]'s screenplay<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lfpress.com/2015/12/10/emma-donoghue-nominated-for-golden-globe-for-her-screenplay-room |title=Emma Donoghue nominated for Golden Globe for her screenplay Room |last=Belanger |first=Joe |date=10 December 2015 |accessdate=27 July 2016 |work=[[The London Free Press]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821033752/http://www.lfpress.com/2015/12/10/emma-donoghue-nominated-for-golden-globe-for-her-screenplay-room |archive-date=August 21, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and [[Jacob Tremblay]]'s performance have also received awards' attention. The film received four nominations for the [[88th Academy Awards]]. ''Room'' was named one of the best films of 2015 by over 50 critics and publications.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-list-the-top-10-movies-of-2015|title=Best of 2015: Film Critic Top Ten Lists|website=Metacritic|accessdate=February 12, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210190401/http://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-list-the-top-10-movies-of-2015|archive-date=December 10, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe film also won nine [[4th Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Awards]], including [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Motion Picture|Best Motion Picture]], [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Director|Best Direction]] for Abramson, [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]] for Donoghue, [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Actor|Best Actor in a Leading Role]] for Tremblay, and [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Actress|Best Actress in a Leading Role]] for Larson.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/radio/q/schedule-for-monday-march-14-2016-1.3490076/q-news-room-wins-big-at-the-canadian-screen-awards-1.3490084 |title=q news: Room wins big at the Canadian Screen Awards |last=Pollock |first=Mitch |date=14 March 2016 |accessdate=25 January 2017 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202025332/http://www.cbc.ca/radio/q/schedule-for-monday-march-14-2016-1.3490076/q-news-room-wins-big-at-the-canadian-screen-awards-1.3490084 |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://playbackonline.ca/2016/03/13/room-cleans-up-at-final-night-of-2016-screenies/ |title=Room cleans up at final night of 2016 Screenies |last=Cummins |first=Julianna |date=13 March 2016 |accessdate=24 January 2017 |work=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103072637/http://playbackonline.ca/2016/03/13/room-cleans-up-at-final-night-of-2016-screenies/ |archive-date=January 3, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> It won seven awards at the [[13th Irish Film & Television Awards]], including Best Film, Director for Abramson, script for Donoghue and International Actress for Larson.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/global/room-irish-film-and-television-awards-1201750117/ |title=Brie Larson's 'Room' Sweeps Irish Film and Television Awards |last=Barraclough |first=Leo |date=11 April 2016 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208122600/http://variety.com/2016/film/global/room-irish-film-and-television-awards-1201750117/ |archive-date=December 8, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://roomthemovie.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|3170832}}\n* {{Mojo title|room2015}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|room_2015}}\n* {{Metacritic film|room-2015}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by Room|Awards for ''Room'']]\n|list =\n{{ACCT Best Picture}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Independent Film}}\n{{TIFF People's Choice Award}}\n{{VFCC Award for Best Canadian Film}}\n{{Warsaw Film Festival Audience Award}}\n}}\n{{Lenny Abrahamson}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Canada|Ireland|United Kingdom|United States|Film}}\n\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2015 drama films]]\n[[Category:2015 independent films]]\n[[Category:A24 films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Best Picture Genie and Canadian Screen Award winners]]\n[[Category:British drama films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British independent films]]\n[[Category:Canadian drama films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian independent films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about kidnapping]]\n[[Category:Films about child abuse]]\n[[Category:Films about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Films based on Irish novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Lenny Abrahamson]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Drama Actress Golden Globe-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films set in Akron, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Irish drama films]]\n[[Category:Irish films]]\n[[Category:Irish independent films]]\n[[Category:Posttraumatic stress disorder in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films about rape]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2015 British-American-Canadian-Irish drama film by Lenny Abrahamson}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name     = Room\n| image    = Room (2015 film).png\n| alt      =\n| caption  = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Lenny Abrahamson]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ed Guiney]]\n* [[David Gross (producer)|David Gross]]\n}}\n| screenplay = [[Emma Donoghue]]\n| based on   = {{based on |[[Room (novel)|Room]]||Emma Donoghue}}\n| starring   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Brie Larson]]\n* [[Jacob Tremblay]]\n* [[Joan Allen]]\n* [[Sean Bridgers]]\n* [[William H. Macy]]\n}}\n| music                = [[Stephen Rennicks]]\n| cinematography       = [[Danny Cohen (cinematographer)|Danny Cohen]]\n| editing              = [[Nathan Nugent]]\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Filmnation Entertainment]]\n* [[Telefilm Canada]]\n* [[Film4 Productions|Film4]]\n* [[Irish Film Board|B\u00f3rd Scann\u00e1n na h\u00c9ireann/Irish Film Board]]\n* Ontario Media Development Corporation\n* [[Element Pictures]]\n* [[No Trace Camping]]\n* Duperele Films\n}}\n| distributor = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Elevation Pictures]] <small>(Canada)</small>\n* [[StudioCanal UK|StudioCanal]] <small>(United Kingdom and Ireland)</small>\n* [[A24 (company)|A24]] <small>(United States)</small>\n}}\n| released    = {{Film date|2015|09|04|[[Telluride Film Festival|Telluride]]|2015|10|16|United States|2015|10|23|Canada|2016|1|15|United Kingdom and Ireland}}\n| runtime     = 118 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 117:39. This rounds to 118 minutes.--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/room-film | title=''ROOM'' | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 5, 2015 | accessdate=November 5, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151224201317/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/room-film | archive-date=December 24, 2015 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| country     = {{Plainlist|\n* Canada\n* Ireland<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/canada-ireland-oscars-brooklyn-room-1.3467850|title=Canada, Ireland lay claim to Oscar nominees Room and Brooklyn|work=[[CBC News]]|date=27 February 2016|accessdate=July 7, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303014859/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/canada-ireland-oscars-brooklyn-room-1.3467850 |archivedate=March 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ifi.ie/room |title=Room |last=Coyne |first=Kevin |accessdate=23 July 2016 |work=[[Irish Film Institute]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817174859/http://www.ifi.ie/room |archive-date=August 17, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/tiff-2015-room-peoples-choice-award-1.3236653 |title=TIFF 2015: Room wins People's Choice Award as festival wraps |last=The Canadian Press |first= |date=September 21, 2015 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[CBC News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509111926/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/tiff-2015-room-peoples-choice-award-1.3236653 |archivedate=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n* United Kingdom\n* United States<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/56427bb42a08b|title=Room BFI website|work=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=1 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001224405/http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/56427bb42a08b|archive-date=October 1, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n| language = English\n| budget   = $13 million<ref name=\"Whipp\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-en-indie-financing-20151229-story.html|title=With indie films such as 'Brooklyn' and 'Room', the creativity often begins with the financing|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 29, 2015|accessdate=February 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712114927/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-en-indie-financing-20151229-story.html|archive-date=July 12, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| gross    = $36.3 million<ref name=\"The Numbers\">{{cite web |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Room-(2015)#tab=summary |title=Room (2016) |website=The Numbers |accessdate=March 28, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405153826/http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Room-(2015)#tab=summary#tab=summary |archive-date=April 5, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Room''''' is a 2015 [[independent film|independent]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Lenny Abrahamson]] and written by [[Emma Donoghue]], based on her [[Room (novel)|2010 novel of the same name]]. It stars [[Brie Larson]] as a woman who has been held captive for seven years and whose 5-year-old son ([[Jacob Tremblay]]) was born in captivity. Their escape allows the boy to experience the outside world for the first time. The film also stars [[Joan Allen]], [[Sean Bridgers]], and [[William H. Macy]].\n\nThe film was a co-production of Canada, Ireland, the United Kingdom, and the United States and was shot in [[Toronto]], with the eponymous set built at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]]. The crew designed each part of the set for the room to be removable to provide access for the crew. Larson researched trauma and nutrition for her part.\n\n''Room'' premiered at the [[Telluride Film Festival]] on September 4, 2015, and later screened at the [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]], where it received the People's Choice Award. The film was theatrically released in Canada on October 23, 2015 by [[Elevation Pictures]] and in the United Kingdom and Ireland on January 15, 2016 by [[StudioCanal UK|StudioCanal]]. It began a [[limited release|limited theatrical run]] in the United States on October 16, 2015 by [[A24 (company)|A24]]. ''Room'' received critical acclaim for Larson's and Tremblay's performances and the storytelling, and grossed $36.3 million on a $13 million budget.\n\nCited as one of the best films of the year, [[List of accolades received by Room|''Room'' received numerous awards and nominations]]. At the [[88th Academy Awards]], ''Room'' received four nominations, including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], and winning [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for Larson. It also won nine [[4th Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Awards]], including [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Motion Picture|Best Motion Picture]], and seven [[13th Irish Film & Television Awards|Irish Film & Television Awards]], including Best Film. Larson won the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] for Best Actress.\n\n==Plot==\nIn [[Akron, Ohio]], 24-year-old Joy Newsome and her 5-year-old son Jack live in a squalid shed they call Room. They share a bed, toilet, bathtub, television, and rudimentary kitchen; the only window is a skylight. They are captives of a man they call \"Old Nick\", Jack's biological father, who abducted Joy seven years prior and routinely rapes her while Jack sleeps in the closet. She tries to stay optimistic for her son but suffers from malnutrition and depression. She allows Jack to believe that only Room and its contents are real, and that the rest of the world exists only on television.\n\nOld Nick tells Joy that he has lost his job and threatens that he may not be able to afford their supplies in the future. That night, Jack is overcome with curiosity and ventures out of the closet while Old Nick is asleep in bed with his mother. Joy is horrified when she awakens and sees their interaction, slapping Old Nick away. As punishment, he cuts their heat and power. Joy decides to tell Jack about the outside world; he reacts with disbelief and incomprehension, but also curiosity. She has Jack fake a fever, hoping that Old Nick will take him to a hospital where he can alert the authorities, but Old Nick says he will return the following day with antibiotics.\n\nJoy wraps Jack in a carpet and has him play dead in the hope that Old Nick will remove him from Room. Falling for the ruse, Old Nick places Jack in the back of his pickup truck and drives through a residential neighborhood. Although stunned by his first exposure to the outside world, Jack jumps from the truck and attracts the attention of a passerby. The police arrive and rescue him. The police discover Joy as well, and take her and Jack to a hospital. Old Nick is captured and arrested.\n\nReunited with her family, Joy learns that her parents have divorced and that her mother has a new partner, Leo. She returns with Jack to her childhood home where her mother and Leo reside. Her father cannot accept Jack as his grandchild and leaves. Jack struggles to adjust to life in the larger world, speaking only to his mother and expressing a desire to return to Room. Joy struggles with anger and depression, lashing out at her mother and becoming worried about Jack's lack of interaction with \"real\" things. At the suggestion of the family's lawyer, Joy agrees to a television interview, but becomes upset when the interviewer questions her decision to keep the newborn Jack instead of asking Old Nick to take him to a hospital. Overwhelmed with guilt, she attempts suicide; Jack finds her unconscious in the bathroom, and she is admitted to a hospital.\n\nJack misses his mother but begins to settle into his new life. He bonds with his new family, meets Leo's dog, Seamus, and makes friends with a boy his age. Believing his long hair will give Joy the strength she needs to recover, Jack has his grandmother cut it for him so he can send it to her. Joy returns home and apologizes, thanking Jack for saving her life again. At Jack's request, they visit Room one last time, escorted by police. Jack is confused; he feels it has shrunk and that it is a different place with the door open. He and Joy say their goodbyes to Room and leave.\n\n==Cast==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Brie Larson]] as Joy \"Ma\" Newsome\n* [[Jacob Tremblay]] as Jack Newsome\n* [[Joan Allen]] as Nancy Newsome\n* [[William H. Macy]] as Robert Newsome\n* [[Sean Bridgers]] as Old Nick\n* [[Tom McCamus]] as Leo\n* [[Amanda Brugel]] as Officer Parker\n* [[Joe Pingue]] as Officer Tom Grabowski\n* [[Cas Anvar]] as Dr. Mittal\n* [[Wendy Crewson]] as Talk Show Hostess\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[File:Irish-Canadian author Emma Donoghue.JPG|upright|thumb|Irish-Canadian author [[Emma Donoghue]] adapted her novel ''[[Room (novel)|Room]]'', served as [[executive producer]] for the film and supported [[Lenny Abrahamson]]'s bid to direct]]\n[[Emma Donoghue]], who also wrote the [[Room (novel)|novel on which the film is based]], wrote the screenplay for the film before the novel was published in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/emma-donoghue-oscars-1.3466881 |title=Oscar-nominated Emma Donoghue wrote Room screenplay before book came out |last=Nathoo |first=Zulekha |date=February 26, 2016 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[CBC News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612105758/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/emma-donoghue-oscars-1.3466881 |archivedate=June 12, 2016 }}</ref> She explained she felt sure the book could be made into a film because of its structured storyline, and received many offers from filmmakers after it was published, which she rejected for creative reasons.<ref name=\"Medley\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/on-set-of-the-room-as-donoghue-watches-her-novel-come-to-filmic-life/article26930003/ |title=On set of the Room as Donoghue watches her novel come to filmic life |last=Medley |first=Mark |date=22 October 2015 |accessdate=26 July 2016 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219195939/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/on-set-of-the-room-as-donoghue-watches-her-novel-come-to-filmic-life/article26930003/ |archive-date=December 19, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Director [[Lenny Abrahamson]] read the novel and sent Donoghue a 10-page [[fan mail|fan letter]] telling her it should be a film, without knowing a screenplay already existed. Donoghue felt the letter demonstrated an understanding of her work and advocated for him as director.<ref name=\"Fear\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/room-how-a-dark-indie-became-2015s-left-field-oscar-contender-20151112 |title='Room': How a Dark Indie Became 2015's Left-Field Oscar Contender |last=Fear |first=David |date=November 12, 2015 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831185410/http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/room-how-a-dark-indie-became-2015s-left-field-oscar-contender-20151112 |archive-date=August 31, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Abrahamson and Donoghue spent one week at her house in [[London, Ontario]] as they revised the screenplay.<ref name=\"Medley\"/> She served as [[executive producer]] and was included in major filmmaking decisions.<ref name=\"Earlyedition\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/emma-donoghue-author-of-bestseller-room-talks-about-turning-her-book-into-a-film-1.3247359 |title=Emma Donoghue, author of bestseller Room, talks about turning her book into a film |last=The Early Edition |date=September 28, 2015 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814154007/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/emma-donoghue-author-of-bestseller-room-talks-about-turning-her-book-into-a-film-1.3247359 |archive-date=August 14, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Abrahamson credited Donoghue with securing funding from Canada, where she is a citizen.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/markets-festivals/room-brie-larson-lenny-abrahamson-toronto-jacob-tremblay1201619031-1201619031/ |title='Room' Director Abrahamson Makes Unlikely Stories Accessible |last=Wise |first=Damon |date=15 October 2015 |accessdate=23 July 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170624090711/http://variety.com/2015/film/markets-festivals/room-brie-larson-lenny-abrahamson-toronto-jacob-tremblay1201619031-1201619031/ |archive-date=June 24, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> She also suggested shooting in [[Toronto]] because it could resemble the United States, and she believed it would be awkward for many Irish filmmakers to work in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/artsfilmtv/emma-donoghue-on-the-room-with-a-different-view-356519.html |title=Emma Donoghue on the Room with a different view |last=Barlow |first=Helen |date=30 September 2015 |accessdate=23 July 2016 |work=[[Irish Examiner]]}}</ref> Canadian producer [[David Gross (producer)|David Gross]] helped persuade his Irish co-producers to shoot in Canada rather than the U.S., saying they could have a longer schedule and more money in Canada.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tiff-2015-why-canadian-productions-822452 |title=TIFF: Why Canadian Co-Productions Thrive in Ontario |last=Vlessing |first=Etan |date=12 September 2015 |accessdate=23 January 2017 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202031512/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tiff-2015-why-canadian-productions-822452 |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:Jacob Tremblay (22859198313) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Canadian child actor [[Jacob Tremblay]] was chosen from dozens of young performers for the part of Jack, and went on to win the [[4th Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Award]] for [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.torontosun.com/2016/03/19/rooms-jacob-tremblay-shows-young-stars-have-come-a-long-way |title=Room's Jacob Tremblay shows young stars have come a long way |last=Slotek |first=Jim |date=19 March 2016 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[Toronto Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916160202/http://www.torontosun.com/2016/03/19/rooms-jacob-tremblay-shows-young-stars-have-come-a-long-way |archive-date=September 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>]]\n[[Emma Watson]], [[Rooney Mara]], [[Shailene Woodley]] and [[Mia Wasikowska]] were considered for the role of Joy.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/brie-larsons-20-year-climb-857011 |title=Brie Larson's 20-Year Climb to Overnight Stardom: I'm 'Totally Out of My Comfort Zone' |last=Sandell |first=Laurie |date=20 January 2016 |accessdate=23 July 2016 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802034854/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/brie-larsons-20-year-climb-857011 |archive-date=August 2, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Brie Larson]] was cast after an associate of Abrahamson suggested he see her in ''[[Short Term 12]]''.<ref name=\"Fear\" /> Larson consulted with a trauma expert and nutritionist for the role,<ref name=\"Harrowing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/brie-larson-why-room-more-lovely-harrowing-226628|title=Brie Larson on why Room is more \"lovely\" than \"harrowing\"|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last1=Bramesco|first1=Charles|accessdate=14 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016023639/http://www.avclub.com/article/brie-larson-why-room-more-lovely-harrowing-226628|archive-date=October 16, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> went on a restrictive diet, and avoided sunlight.<ref name=\"Ahearn\"/> She said she saw the film less as a crime story and more of \"a story of love and freedom and perseverance and what it feels like to grow up and become your own person\".<ref name=\"Harrowing\" />\n\nThe filmmakers considered dozens of child actors for Jack before choosing seven-year-old [[Jacob Tremblay]] from [[Vancouver]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/room-builds-buzz-awards-1.3285386 |title=Room, starring Brie Larson and Jacob Tremblay, earns Oscar buzz despite dark subject matter |last=Sumanac-Johnson |first=Deana |date=October 23, 2015 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[CBC News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320051119/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/room-builds-buzz-awards-1.3285386 |archivedate=20 March 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"Ahearn\"/> Tremblay said his part was not hard \"because I was playing a happy child\" unaware of the sinister nature of Room.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/in-contention/room-brie-larson-praises-jacob-tremblay-1201652086/ |title='Room's' Brie Larson, Joan Allen Praise Breakout Star Jacob Tremblay (Video) |last=Riley |first=Jenelle |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205184412/https://variety.com/2015/film/in-contention/room-brie-larson-praises-jacob-tremblay-1201652086/ |archive-date=February 5, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> As he was too young to read the whole screenplay, each scene was explained to him one by one.<ref name=\"Ahearn\"/> Tremblay wore a [[wig]] made from human hair.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/144256-did-jacob-tremblay-wear-a-wig-in-room-that-long-hair-was-very-convincing |title=Did Jacob Tremblay Wear A Wig In 'Room'? That Long Hair Was Very Convincing |last=McGahan |first=Michelle |date=February 25, 2016 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708075302/http://www.bustle.com/articles/144256-did-jacob-tremblay-wear-a-wig-in-room-that-long-hair-was-very-convincing |archive-date=July 8, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> According to [[Joan Allen]], who played Nancy, Larson and Tremblay met for over three weeks to build a \"very tight, obviously critical, close relationship\", before the Room scenes were shot over five weeks. Allen arrived in Toronto later and met Tremblay, \"But we didn't want him to become too familiar with me because that's not what the story is.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/joan-allen-on-room/ |title=Joan Allen on 'Room' |last=Freshwater |first=Lori |date=December 20, 2015 |accessdate=July 23, 2016 |work=[[Los Angeles Review of Books]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812113129/https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/joan-allen-on-room/ |archive-date=August 12, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn preparing for her own role, Allen did not consult real mothers of kidnapped children, but said she reflected on her own experiences \"in a mall when my daughter was little and I look around and within a flash she's not there\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://parade.com/459480/walterscott/did-joan-allen-do-research-for-her-role-in-room/ |title=Did Joan Allen Do Research for her Role in Room? |last=Scott |first=Walter |date=26 February 2016 |accessdate=29 July 2016 |work=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817220742/http://parade.com/459480/walterscott/did-joan-allen-do-research-for-her-role-in-room/ |archive-date=August 17, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Canadian actor [[Tom McCamus]] auditioned for the part of Old Nick before being cast as Leo.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-en-mn-small-roles-20151222-story.html |title=Four actors leave big impressions with small roles |date=22 December 2015 |accessdate=29 July 2016 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809200807/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-en-mn-small-roles-20151222-story.html |archive-date=August 9, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The actors improvised some lines, with Donoghue saying they created \"speech patterns more natural-sounding than I could have written, and produced some brilliant new lines that ended up in the film.\"<ref name=\"Earlyedition\" />\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:TorontoPinewoodStudios.JPG|thumb|The only ''Room'' set was built at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]] by production designer [[Ethan Tobman]]]]\nAbrahamson used only one Room set, wanting to create an authentic experience for Tremblay.<ref name=\"Tapley\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/in-contention/room-set-10-feet-production-designer-cinematographer-1201643947/ |title='Room': Creating a Whole World in a 10-Foot Space |last=Tapley |first=Kristopher |date=19 November 2015 |accessdate=27 July 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205184837/https://variety.com/2015/film/in-contention/room-set-10-feet-production-designer-cinematographer-1201643947/ |archive-date=February 5, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The set, built on a soundstage at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]],<ref name=\"Tapley\"/> was {{convert|11|\u00d7|11|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Buxton\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/lenny-abrahamson-room-bathtub_us_56743d34e4b014efe0d53b72 |title=Why 'Room' Director Lenny Abrahamson Spent A Month Hiding In A Bathtub |last=Buxton |first=Ryan |date=December 18, 2015 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802192250/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/lenny-abrahamson-room-bathtub_us_56743d34e4b014efe0d53b72 |archive-date=August 2, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Montreal]] production designer [[Ethan Tobman]] set out with the idea \"that every square inch of Room needed to have a backstory\".<ref name=\"Brunhuber\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/room-set-design-trauma-1.3460087 |title=Oscar-nominated Room required painstaking precision from cast and crew |last=Brunhuber |first=Kim |date=February 25, 2016 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[CBC News]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612172620/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/room-set-design-trauma-1.3460087 |archivedate=12 June 2016}}</ref> To fit the crew and equipment into the small space, he made each piece of the set removable. However, as Abrahamson and cinematographer [[Danny Cohen (cinematographer)|Danny Cohen]] wanted the camera to always shoot scenes from inside Room, the lens was always positioned within the set even if the rest of the camera was outside.<ref name=\"Brunhuber\" /> There were as many as eight cameramen at a time inside the Room set with Larson and Tremblay.<ref name=\"Ahearn\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.news1130.com/2015/10/21/brie-larson-on-room-role-bonding-with-clever-young-co-star-jacob-tremblay/ |title=Brie Larson on 'Room' role, bonding with clever young co-star Jacob Tremblay |last=Ahearn |first=Victoria |date=October 21, 2015 |accessdate=March 17, 2017 |publisher=[[The Canadian Press]] |work=[[CKWX]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318023312/http://www.news1130.com/2015/10/21/brie-larson-on-room-role-bonding-with-clever-young-co-star-jacob-tremblay/ |archive-date=March 18, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The actors also made the [[Theatrical property|props]] decorating the set.<ref name=\"Tapley\"/>\n\nBecause the scenes set outside Room were filmed after the scenes inside, the crew was initially eager to leave the cramped space, expecting that the rest of the film would be easy.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.avclub.com/article/brie-larson-why-room-more-lovely-harrowing-226628 |title=Brie Larson on why Room is more 'lovely' than 'harrowing' |last=Bramesco |first=Charles |date=14 October 2015 |accessdate=27 July 2016 |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016023639/http://www.avclub.com/article/brie-larson-why-room-more-lovely-harrowing-226628 |archive-date=October 16, 2015 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> However, they had difficulty adjusting to the cold weather, traffic and crowds in Toronto.<ref name=\"Buxton\" /> Cohen remarked that upon returning to the Room set for the final scene, the set appeared smaller to the crew.<ref name=\"Lytal\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-en-danny-cohen-danish-girl-20151203-story.html |title=The cinematographer of 'The Danish Girl' and 'Room' details shooting such 'extreme opposites' |last=Lytal |first=Cristy |date=3 December 2015 |accessdate=27 July 2016 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817051052/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-en-danny-cohen-danish-girl-20151203-story.html |archive-date=August 17, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nCohen used a [[Panavision cameras|Panavision Primos]] lens on a [[Red Digital Cinema|Red Epic Dragon]] camera, saying \"The Primos and using Kino Flos, which is more akin to fluorescent lighting, gave ''Room'' a certain texture, a certain look.\"<ref name=\"Lytal\"/> [[Principal photography]] began on 10 November 2014<ref name=\"Filming\">{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=AFM: William H. Macy, Joan Allen Join Brie Larson's 'Room'|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/afm-william-h-macy-joan-allen-join-brie-larsons-room-1201352555/|accessdate=17 November 2014|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=10 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206002532/https://variety.com/2014/film/news/afm-william-h-macy-joan-allen-join-brie-larsons-room-1201352555/|archive-date=February 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and ended on 15 December 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=On The Set for 12/15/14: JJ Abrams Wraps 'The Cellar', Tom Hiddleston Finishes 'I Saw the Light' & More|url=http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-121514-jj-abrams-wraps-the-cellar-tom-hiddleston-finishes-i-saw-the-light-more/|accessdate=16 December 2014|website=ssninsider.com|date=15 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924105339/http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-121514-jj-abrams-wraps-the-cellar-tom-hiddleston-finishes-i-saw-the-light-more/|archivedate=September 24, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\nEditor [[Nathan Nugent]] served as second-unit director.<ref name=\"Murphy\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/23/movies/below-the-line-editing-room.html?_r=0 |title=Below the Line: Editing 'Room' |last=Murphy |first=Mekado |date=23 December 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2017 |work=[[The New York Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103133855/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/23/movies/below-the-line-editing-room.html?_r=0 |archive-date=January 3, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He described his editing of ''Room'' as simplistic, keeping the acting intact, while working in [[Dublin]] for five months.<ref name=\"Grobar\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/nathan-nugent-editor-room-interview-oscars-2015-1201653335/ |title=Editor Nathan Nugent On 'Room': 'We Tried Not To Get In The Way Of The Great Performances' |last=Grobar |first=Matt |date=7 December 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2017 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621143548/https://deadline.com/2015/12/nathan-nugent-editor-room-interview-oscars-2015-1201653335/ |archive-date=June 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> However, Tremblay's part was filmed in numerous takes so Tremblay could give variations of his performances of specific lines, so Abrahamson and Nugent had to assemble and splice the different takes in the editing process.<ref name=\"Murphy\"/>\n\n==Release==\nPrior to production, [[A24 (company)|A24]] acquired U.S. distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ford|first1=Rebecca|title=Cannes: Brie Larson Drama 'Room' Goes to A24 Films|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-brie-larson-drama-room-705279|accessdate=17 November 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=18 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116224402/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-brie-larson-drama-room-705279|archive-date=January 16, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''Room'' had its world premiere on September 4, 2015, at the [[Telluride Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elementpictures.ie/news/lenny-abrahamsons-room-to-have-world-premiere-at-the-telluride-film-festival/|title=Lenny Abrahamson's ''Room'' to have world premiere at the Telluride Film Festival|website=Elementpictures.ie|date=September 4, 2015|accessdate=February 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304200053/http://elementpictures.ie/news/lenny-abrahamsons-room-to-have-world-premiere-at-the-telluride-film-festival/|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It went on to screen in the Special Presentations section at the [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"ScreenDaily\">{{cite web|url = http://www.screendaily.com/toronto-world-premieres-for-trumbo-demolition-the-program/5090990.article?blocktitle=LATEST-FILM-NEWS&contentID=40562#|title = Toronto to open with 'Demolition'; world premieres for 'Trumbo', 'The Program'|date = 28 July 2015|accessdate = 28 July 2015|work = [[Screen Daily]]|archive-url = https://archive.is/20150729193951/http://www.screendaily.com/toronto-world-premieres-for-trumbo-demolition-the-program/5090990.article?blocktitle=LATEST-FILM-NEWS&contentID=40562%23|archive-date = July 29, 2015|url-status = live|df = mdy-all}}</ref> and at the [[BFI London Film Festival|London Film Festival]], on October 11, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whatson.bfi.org.uk/lff/Online/default.asp?BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::permalink=room|title=Room|website=[[BFI London Film Festival]]|accessdate=February 13, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311045648/https://whatson.bfi.org.uk/lff/Online/default.asp?BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::permalink=room|archive-date=March 11, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film began a [[limited release]] on October 15, 2015.<ref name=\"Variety1\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/brie-larson-room-october-release-1201552606/ |title=Brie Larson's 'Room' Set for Oct 16 Release |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=29 July 2015 |accessdate=16 September 2015 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205184834/https://variety.com/2015/film/news/brie-larson-room-october-release-1201552606/ |archive-date=February 5, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''Room'' was released in the United Kingdom and Ireland on January 15, 2016, by [[StudioCanal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/a6800516.html |title=Room: Poignant exclusive clip sees Brie Larson make a birthday cake for the most adorable five-year-old |work=[[The Independent]] |first=Jess |last=Denham |date=7 January 2016 |accessdate=18 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930175633/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/a6800516.html |archive-date=September 30, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jan/17/room-review-lenny-abrahamson-brie-larson-jacob-tremblay |title=Room review \u2013 to see the world within four walls |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Mark |last=Kermode |authorlink=Mark Kermode |date=17 January 2016 |accessdate=18 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620014403/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jan/17/room-review-lenny-abrahamson-brie-larson-jacob-tremblay |archive-date=June 20, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/oscar-nominations-room-lenny-abrahamson-ed-guiney-brie-larson-michael-fassbender-emma-stone-olivia-colman-1201683286/ |title=Oscar Nominations: Friendship Is Crucial Element For 'Room's Lenny Abrahamson And Ed Guiney |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |last1=Jaafar |first1=Ali |last2=Fleming |first2=Mike Jr. |date=14 January 2016 |accessdate=18 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318173154/http://deadline.com/2016/01/oscar-nominations-room-lenny-abrahamson-ed-guiney-brie-larson-michael-fassbender-emma-stone-olivia-colman-1201683286/ |archive-date=March 18, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> It went into [[wide release]] on January 22, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/ride-along-2-begins-to-zoom-in-thursday-previews-box-office-1201683644/ |title='Ride Along 2' Continues No. 1 Journey With $41.5M; '13 Hours' Clocks $19.65M \u2013 Monday Update |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=18 January 2016 |accessdate=28 February 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117101525/http://deadline.com/2016/01/ride-along-2-begins-to-zoom-in-thursday-previews-box-office-1201683644/ |archive-date=January 17, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe film was released by [[Lionsgate]] on [[DVD-Video|DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] in the United States on March 1, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/news/a42591/movies-stream-march-2016/ |title=Here Are the Must-Stream Movies of March 2016 |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |last=Schager |first=Nick |date=1 March 2016 |accessdate=18 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319022741/http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/news/a42591/movies-stream-march-2016/ |archive-date=March 19, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> It was released on DVD and Blu-ray in UK and Ireland in May 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irishnews.com/arts/film/2016/05/20/news/dvd-of-the-week-room-524924/ |title=DVD of the week: Room |last=Roy |first=David |date=20 May 2016 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[The Irish News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816142250/http://www.irishnews.com/arts/film/2016/05/20/news/dvd-of-the-week-room-524924/ |archive-date=August 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nAfter its U.S. release on October 16, 2015, ''Room'' played in a peak of 198 theaters from December 11 to 13, and grossed $5,166,724 before its Academy Award nominations were announced, making it one of the lowest-grossing Best Picture nominees in years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/01/room-best-picture-gross-box-office.html |title=Room Was Nominated for Best Picture Despite Making Historically Little Money |last=Lincoln |first=Kevin |date=January 14, 2016 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[Vulture.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819195851/http://www.vulture.com/2016/01/room-best-picture-gross-box-office.html |archive-date=August 19, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Initial box office under-performance came as a surprise to Canada's [[Elevation Pictures]], since winning the People's Choice Award at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] was usually a predictor of financial success.<ref name=\"Houpt\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/the-marketing-quest-to-turn-room-into-a-populist-hit/article28321890/ |title=The marketing quest to turn Room into a populist hit |last=Houpt |first=Simon |date=21 January 2016 |accessdate=26 July 2016 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515081409/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/the-marketing-quest-to-turn-room-into-a-populist-hit/article28321890/ |archive-date=May 15, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> However, the nominations gave the film a boost at the box office, and after opening in the [[Republic of Ireland]] on 15 January, it initially made \u20ac200,000 at 50 theatres.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/technow/movies/room-triumphs-at-the-box-office-376832.html |title=Room triumphs at the box office |last= |first= |date=January 18, 2016 |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |work=[[Irish Examiner]]}}</ref>\n\nA month after its release in Ireland, it had grossed more than \u20ac1 million nationwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irishfilmboard.ie/irish_film_industry/news/Congratulations_to_the_Irish_Films_BROOKLYN_amp_ROOM_on_Winning_BAFTA_AWARDS/3021 |title=Congratulations to the Irish Films Brooklyn & Room on Winning BAFTA Awards |publisher=[[Irish Film Board]] |accessdate=23 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314222927/http://www.irishfilmboard.ie/irish_film_industry/news/Congratulations_to_the_Irish_Films_BROOKLYN_amp_ROOM_on_Winning_BAFTA_AWARDS/3021 |archive-date=March 14, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On 24 April, ''Room'' completed its run having grossed an estimated $14.7 million in North America and $20.7 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $35.4 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=room2015.htm |title=Room (2016) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=23 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724064437/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=room2015.htm |archive-date=July 24, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> on a $13 million budget.<ref name=\"Whipp\"/>\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{Anchor|Critics|Critical response}}\n[[File:Brie Larson by Gage Skidmore.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Brie Larson]]'s performance as Joy \"Ma\" Newsome received widespread acclaim and earned her the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]]]]\n\n''Room'' received widespread critical acclaim. [[Review aggregator|Review aggregation]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a rating of 93%, based on 303 reviews, with an average rating of 8.46/10. The site's critical consensus states, \"Led by incredible work from Brie Larson and Jacob Tremblay, ''Room'' makes for an unforgettably harrowing\u2014and undeniably rewarding\u2014experience.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/room_2015/ | title=Room (2015) | work=Rotten Tomatoes | publisher=[[Flixster]] | accessdate=3 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423060000/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/room_2015/ | archive-date=April 23, 2016 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gives the film a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 86 out of 100, based on reviews from 43 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/room-2015 | title=Room Reviews | work=Metacritic | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=9 December 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912232938/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/room-2015 | archive-date=September 12, 2015 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Todd McCarthy]] from ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote, \"Overall, it's a decent shot at a tall target, but real credit is due the lead actors, with Larson expanding beyond the already considerable range she's previously shown with an exceedingly dimensional performance in a role that calls for running the gamut, and Tremblay always convincing without ever becoming cloying.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/room-telluride-review-820547|title='Room': Telluride Review|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Todd|last=McCarthy|date=4 September 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212004042/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/room-telluride-review-820547|archive-date=December 12, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Eric Kohn of ''[[IndieWire]]'' stated, \"Brie Larson and newcomer Jacob Tremblay['s]... textured performances turn outrageous circumstances into a tense and surprisingly credible survival tale.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/telluride-review-brie-larson-is-a-revelation-alongside-stunning-newcomer-jacob-tremblay-in-room-20150904|title=Telluride Review: Brie Larson is a Revelation Alongside Stunning Newcomer Jacob Tremblay in 'Room'|work=Indiewire|first=Eric|last=Kohn|date=4 September 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225151502/http://www.indiewire.com/article/telluride-review-brie-larson-is-a-revelation-alongside-stunning-newcomer-jacob-tremblay-in-room-20150904|archive-date=December 25, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' called the film \"the most impressive piece of filmmaking I've seen in 2015, and one of the best movies of the decade\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Room|url=http://roomthemovie.com/#/press|website=Room the Movie (official website) |accessdate=January 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160104091912/http://roomthemovie.com/#/press#/press|archive-date=January 4, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Rex Reed]] said ''Room'' is \"so powerful and unforgettable that it must be seen\" but \"too grim and heartbreaking for some viewers\".<ref name=\"Houpt\"/>\n\nThe central performances of Brie Larson and Jacob Tremblay have received critical acclaim. Joe Morgenstern of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' said \"this drama is as big as all outdoors in scope; poetic and profound in its exploration of the senses; blessed with two transcendent performances, by Brie Larson and Jacob Tremblay; and as elegantly wrought as any film that has come our way in a very long while.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Morgenstern|first1=Joe|title='Room': Downsized Space, Vibrant Life|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/room-downsized-space-vibrant-life-1444933986|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=February 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318173951/https://www.wsj.com/articles/room-downsized-space-vibrant-life-1444933986|archive-date=March 18, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' wrote, \"All you need to know is that the performances of Larson and Tremblay will blow you away. Tremblay is a child actor incapable of a false move. And Larson, so good in ''[[Short Term 12]]'', is magnificent, finding a way into Joy's bruised psyche that tears at your heart.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Travers|first1=Peter|title=Room|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/room-20151015|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=February 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901194824/http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/room-20151015|archive-date=September 1, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe film received positive reviews in its countries of origin, with Barry Hertz of Canada's ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' writing \"''Room'' is a film of tiny little miracles,\" finding it uplifting, praising Larson's performance and referring to Tremblay as \"a wide-eyed wonder who is always genuine\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/film-reviews/room-uplifting-tale-of-miracles-and-love-bound-by-a-horrific-kidnapping/article26936865/ |title=Room: Uplifting tale of miracles and love bound by a horrific kidnapping |last=Hertz |first=Barry |date=October 23, 2015 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126173811/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/film-reviews/room-uplifting-tale-of-miracles-and-love-bound-by-a-horrific-kidnapping/article26936865/ |archive-date=November 26, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Chris Knight for the ''[[National Post]]'' called Tremblay \"preternaturally talented\", and said ''Room'' \"works on a tiny canvas, but in doing so it emphasizes that great things can be accomplished in tight spaces\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/arts/movies/room-review-how-a-single-room-acts-as-an-allegory-for-the-chamber-of-our-own-minds |title=Room review: How a single room acts as an allegory for the chamber of our own minds |last=Knight |first=Chris |date=22 October 2015 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[National Post]] |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20160320175910/http://news.nationalpost.com/arts/movies/room-review-how-a-single-room-acts-as-an-allegory-for-the-chamber-of-our-own-minds |archive-date=March 20, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Liz Braun of the ''[[Toronto Sun]]'' said Jack's narration made the Room scenes \"joyful\" as well as claustrophobic, and that Larson and Tremblay's performances are \"completely engaging\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.torontosun.com/2015/10/22/room-review-film-finds-uplifting-message-in-chilling-tale-of-captivity |title='Room' review: Film finds uplifting message in chilling tale of captivity |last=Braun |first=Liz |date=22 October 2015 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[Toronto Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916154557/http://www.torontosun.com/2015/10/22/room-review-film-finds-uplifting-message-in-chilling-tale-of-captivity |archive-date=September 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Linda Barnard of the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' called ''Room'' \"equally tender and chilling\",<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2015/10/22/drama-room-chilling-yet-uplifting-review.html |title=Drama Room chilling yet uplifting: review |last=Barnard |first=Linda |date=22 October 2015 |accessdate=27 July 2016 |work=[[Toronto Star]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816173612/https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2015/10/22/drama-room-chilling-yet-uplifting-review.html |archive-date=August 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In Ireland, Donald Clarke of ''[[The Irish Times]]'' gave the film five stars, calling it \"harrowing\", and concluded, \"We are left with a film that manages a degree of optimism in the most unpromising circumstances. It is a substantial achievement.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/room-review-home-is-where-the-room-is-1.2496697 |title=Room review: home is where the room is |last=Clarke |first=Donald |date=14 January 2016 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160213091807/http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/room-review-home-is-where-the-room-is-1.2496697 |archive-date=February 13, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Daniel Anderson, writing for the ''[[Irish Examiner]]'', called ''Room'' \"an utterly unique tale which has seen the filmmaker deservedly thrust onto the world stage\", but also \"bleak\" and \"difficult to recommend\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/technow/movies/room-review-375990.html |title=Room review |last=Anderson |first=Daniel |date=13 January 2016 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[Irish Examiner]]}}</ref>\n\nDissenting, [[Kyle Smith]] of the ''[[New York Post]]'' wrote \"The script ... doesn't illuminate what kind of internal damage might be wrought by being held prisoner for seven years: On-screen it simply looks like Joy has a case of the sads.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=In 'Room', Brie Larson tries to win a no-makeup Oscar|url=https://nypost.com/2015/10/14/in-room-brie-larson-tries-to-win-a-no-makeup-oscar/|website=The New York Post|accessdate=13 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201032024/https://nypost.com/2015/10/14/in-room-brie-larson-tries-to-win-a-no-makeup-oscar/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Matthew Lickona of the ''[[San Diego Reader]]'' also called it \"a cowardly movie about brave people\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sandiegoreader.com/movies/room/# |title=Room |last=Lickona |first=Matthew |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[San Diego Reader]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813163206/http://www.sandiegoreader.com/movies/room/ |archive-date=August 13, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{main|List of accolades received by Room}}\n''Room'' has received many awards and nominations. [[Brie Larson]]'s performance in particular has been singled out for awards, with the [[National Board of Review]],<ref name=NBR>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/2015/12/national-board-of-review-announces-2015-award-winners/|title=National Board of Review Announces 2015 Award Winners|website=[[National Board of Review]]|accessdate=July 17, 2016|date=December 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418070538/http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/2015/12/national-board-of-review-announces-2015-award-winners/|archive-date=April 18, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Chicago Film Critics Association|Chicago Film Critics]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Gire|first=Dann|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20151216/entlife/151219073/|title='Mad Max: Fury Road' wins best picture from Chicago Film Critics|work=Daily Herald|date=December 17, 2015|accessdate=December 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218061449/http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20151216/entlife/151219073/|archive-date=December 18, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and various other film critic organizations awarding her Best Actress. Larson has also won several major awards, including the [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Academy Award]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35313266|title=Oscars 2016: Winners list in full|website=[[BBC News]]|date=February 28, 2016|accessdate=February 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225011630/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35313266|archive-date=February 25, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Critics' Choice Movie Awards|Critics' Choice Award]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Rosen|first=Christopher|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/01/17/critics-choice-awards-2016-winners-list|title=Critics' Choice Awards 2016 winners: Spotlight, Mad Max, Leonardo DiCaprio, and more|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=January 17, 2016|accessdate=February 17, 2016|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6ecsPvoj9?url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/01/17/critics-choice-awards-2016-winners-list|archive-date=January 18, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Screen Actors Guild]],<ref name=SAG>{{cite web|url=http://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/22nd-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards|title=The 22nd Annual Screen Actors Guild Awards|website=[[Screen Actors Guild Awards]]|accessdate=February 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024171400/http://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/22nd-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards|archive-date=October 24, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[British Academy Film Awards|BAFTA Award]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35260399|title=Bafta Film Awards 2016: Winners|website=BBC News|date=February 14, 2016|accessdate=May 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160214053026/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35260399|archive-date=February 14, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the [[Golden Globe Award]] for Best Actress.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-et-mn-golden-globes-2016-nominees-winners-list-story.html|title=Golden Globes 2016: Complete list of nominees|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=December 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202175445/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-et-mn-golden-globes-2016-nominees-winners-list-story.html|archive-date=December 2, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Emma Donoghue]]'s screenplay<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lfpress.com/2015/12/10/emma-donoghue-nominated-for-golden-globe-for-her-screenplay-room |title=Emma Donoghue nominated for Golden Globe for her screenplay Room |last=Belanger |first=Joe |date=10 December 2015 |accessdate=27 July 2016 |work=[[The London Free Press]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821033752/http://www.lfpress.com/2015/12/10/emma-donoghue-nominated-for-golden-globe-for-her-screenplay-room |archive-date=August 21, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and [[Jacob Tremblay]]'s performance have also received awards' attention. The film received four nominations for the [[88th Academy Awards]]. ''Room'' was named one of the best films of 2015 by over 50 critics and publications.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-list-the-top-10-movies-of-2015|title=Best of 2015: Film Critic Top Ten Lists|website=Metacritic|accessdate=February 12, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210190401/http://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-list-the-top-10-movies-of-2015|archive-date=December 10, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe film also won nine [[4th Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Awards]], including [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Motion Picture|Best Motion Picture]], [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Director|Best Direction]] for Abramson, [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]] for Donoghue, [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Actor|Best Actor in a Leading Role]] for Tremblay, and [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Actress|Best Actress in a Leading Role]] for Larson.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/radio/q/schedule-for-monday-march-14-2016-1.3490076/q-news-room-wins-big-at-the-canadian-screen-awards-1.3490084 |title=q news: Room wins big at the Canadian Screen Awards |last=Pollock |first=Mitch |date=14 March 2016 |accessdate=25 January 2017 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202025332/http://www.cbc.ca/radio/q/schedule-for-monday-march-14-2016-1.3490076/q-news-room-wins-big-at-the-canadian-screen-awards-1.3490084 |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://playbackonline.ca/2016/03/13/room-cleans-up-at-final-night-of-2016-screenies/ |title=Room cleans up at final night of 2016 Screenies |last=Cummins |first=Julianna |date=13 March 2016 |accessdate=24 January 2017 |work=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103072637/http://playbackonline.ca/2016/03/13/room-cleans-up-at-final-night-of-2016-screenies/ |archive-date=January 3, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> It won seven awards at the [[13th Irish Film & Television Awards]], including Best Film, Director for Abramson, script for Donoghue and International Actress for Larson.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/global/room-irish-film-and-television-awards-1201750117/ |title=Brie Larson's 'Room' Sweeps Irish Film and Television Awards |last=Barraclough |first=Leo |date=11 April 2016 |accessdate=24 July 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208122600/http://variety.com/2016/film/global/room-irish-film-and-television-awards-1201750117/ |archive-date=December 8, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://roomthemovie.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|3170832}}\n* {{Mojo title|room2015}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|room_2015}}\n* {{Metacritic film|room-2015}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for ''Room''\n|list =\n{{ACCT Best Picture}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Independent Film}}\n{{TIFF People's Choice Award}}\n{{VFCC Award for Best Canadian Film}}\n{{Warsaw Film Festival Audience Award}}\n}}\n{{Lenny Abrahamson}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Canada|Ireland|United Kingdom|United States|Film}}\n\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2015 drama films]]\n[[Category:2015 independent films]]\n[[Category:A24 films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Best Picture Genie and Canadian Screen Award winners]]\n[[Category:British drama films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British independent films]]\n[[Category:Canadian drama films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian independent films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about kidnapping]]\n[[Category:Films about child abuse]]\n[[Category:Films about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Films based on Irish novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Lenny Abrahamson]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Drama Actress Golden Globe-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films set in Akron, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Irish drama films]]\n[[Category:Irish films]]\n[[Category:Irish independent films]]\n[[Category:Posttraumatic stress disorder in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films about rape]]\n", "name_user": "Ribbet32", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Room_(2015_film)"}
{"title_page": "Juanjo (footballer, born 1981)", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Serrano|Mac\u00edas}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Juanjo\n| image = \n| full_name = Juan Jos\u00e9 Serrano Mac\u00edas\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1981|10|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Calamonte]], Spain\n| height = 1.84 m\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| currentclub = [[CD Santa Amalia|Santa Amalia]]\n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[M\u00e9rida UD|M\u00e9rida]]\n| years1 = 2000\u20132001 | clubs1 = [[M\u00e9rida UD|M\u00e9rida Promesas]] | caps1 = 36 | goals1 = 26\n| years2 = 2001\u20132003 | clubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B]] | caps2 = 40 | goals2 = 3\n| years3 = 2003\u20132004 | clubs3 = [[AD Alcorc\u00f3n|Alcorc\u00f3n]] | caps3 = 30 | goals3 = 5\n| years4 = 2004\u20132005 | clubs4 = [[CD D\u00edter Zafra|D\u00edter Zafra]] | caps4 = 34 | goals4 = 6\n| years5 = 2005\u20132006 | clubs5 = [[Real Ja\u00e9n|Ja\u00e9n]] | caps5 = 31 | goals5 = 4\n| years6 = 2006\u20132007 | clubs6 = [[UD Lanzarote|Lanzarote]] | caps6 = 36 | goals6 = 14\n| years7 = 2007\u20132008 | clubs7 = [[Mazarr\u00f3n CF|Mazarr\u00f3n]] | caps7 = 33 | goals7 = 3\n| years8 = 2008\u20132009 | clubs8 = [[UB Conquense|Conquense]] | caps8 = 29 | goals8 = 2\n| years9 = 2009\u20132010 | clubs9 = [[CF Villanovense|Villanovense]] | caps9 = 36 | goals9 = 21\n| years10 = 2010\u20132011 | clubs10 = [[CD Guadalajara (Spain)|Guadalajara]] | caps10 = 37 | goals10 = 20\n| years11 = 2011\u20132013 | clubs11 = [[Granada CF|Granada]] | caps11 = 0 | goals11 = 0\n| years12 = 2011\u20132012 | clubs12 = \u2192 [[C\u00e1diz CF|C\u00e1diz]] (loan) | caps12 = 29 | goals12 = 9\n| years13 = 2012\u20132013 | clubs13 = \u2192 [[UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s|Logron\u00e9s]] (loan) | caps13 = 13 | goals13 = 0\n| years14 = 2013 | clubs14 = [[CD Guadalajara (Spain)|Guadalajara]] | caps14 = 16 | goals14 = 4\n| years15 = 2013\u20132014 | clubs15 = [[CD Lugo|Lugo]] | caps15 = 16 | goals15 = 0\n| years16 = 2014\u20132015 | clubs16 = [[CD Mirand\u00e9s|Mirand\u00e9s]] | caps16 = 31 | goals16 = 2\n| years17 = 2015\u20132017 | clubs17 = [[CF Villanovense|Villanovense]] | caps17 = 59 | goals17 = 9\n| years18 = 2017\u2013 | clubs18 = [[CD Santa Amalia|Santa Amalia]] | caps18 = 38 | goals18 = 15\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| club-update = 25 November 2018\n}}\n\n'''Juan Jos\u00e9 Serrano Mac\u00edas''' (born 3 October 1981), commonly known as '''Juanjo''', is a Spanish [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[CD Santa Amalia]] as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]].\n\n==Club career==\nJuanjo was born in [[Calamonte]], [[Province of Badajoz]].  After starting his senior career with local [[M\u00e9rida UD]]'s [[reserve team]], he went on to spend one full decade in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]. He first represented at that level [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B]], [[AD Alcorc\u00f3n]], [[CD D\u00edter Zafra]], [[Real Ja\u00e9n]], [[UD Lanzarote]], [[Mazarr\u00f3n CF]], [[UB Conquense]], [[CF Villanovense]] and [[CD Guadalajara (Spain)|CD Guadalajara]].\n\nJuanjo joined [[La Liga]] club [[Granada CF]] in 2011 but never represented it officially, being loaned to [[C\u00e1diz CF]] and [[UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s]] in the same tier. On 20 January 2013 he terminated his contract and returned to Guadalajara,<ref>[http://www.granadacf.es/index.php?seccion=leer_mas&id_noticia=1382 Juanjo Serrano traspasado al Guadalajara (Juanjo Serrano transferred to Guadalajara)]; Granada CF, 21 January 2013 (in Spanish)</ref> signing a two-and-a-half-year deal.<ref>[http://www.deportivoguadalajara.es/web/juanjo-regresa-al-club-deportivo-guadalajara/ Juanjo regresa al Club Deportivo Guadalajara (Juanjo returns to Club Deportivo Guadalajara)]; CD Guadalajara, 20 January 2013 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nAged already 31, Juanjo made his first appearance in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] on 26 January 2013, starting in a 0\u20132 away loss against [[Girona FC]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/01/26/futbol/2adivision/1359219403.html El Girona rompe la mala racha (Girona end negative streak)]; [[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]], 26 January 2013 (in Spanish)</ref> His first goal with the professionals came on 30 March as he scored the only at [[UD Las Palmas]],<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/03/30/futbol/2adivision/1364670407.html Juanjo silencia a Las Palmas en su estadio (Juanjo silents Las Palmas away)]; Marca, 30 March 2013 (in Spanish)</ref> and he netted a second the following weekend, contributing to a 3\u20131 home victory over [[C\u00f3rdoba CF]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/04/07/futbol/2adivision/1365357493.html El Deportivo se aferra a Segunda y apaga las ilusiones del C\u00f3rdoba (Deportivo cling on to ''Segunda'' and dim C\u00f3rdoba's hopes)]; Marca, 7 April 2013 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nOn 23 August 2013, Juanjo moved to fellow league side [[CD Lugo]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/08/23/futbol/equipos/lugo/1377274420.html El Lugo incorpora para el ataque a Juanjo (Lugo add Juanjo to attack)]; Marca, 23 August 2013 (in Spanish)</ref> He totalled only 603 minutes of action in his [[2013\u201314 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|first and only season]], and subsequently joined [[CD Mirand\u00e9s]] also of the second division.<ref>[http://www.cdmirandes.com/-/juan-jose-serrano-macias-juanjo-nuevo-fichaje-del-c-d-mirandes Juan Jos\u00e9 Serrano Macias \"Juanjo\" nuevo fichaje del C.D. Mirand\u00e9s (Juan Jos\u00e9 Serrano Macias \"Juanjo\" new signing of C.D. Mirand\u00e9s)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826121239/http://www.cdmirandes.com/-/juan-jose-serrano-macias-juanjo-nuevo-fichaje-del-c-d-mirandes|date=26 August 2014}}; CD Mirand\u00e9s, 30 June 2014 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|400089}}\n*{{Futbolme|19226}}\n*{{LaPreferente|73601<!-- C7372 -->}}\n*{{Soccerway|juan-jose-serrano-macias/60098}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Juanjo}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Tierra de M\u00e9rida - Vegas Bajas]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Extremaduran footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B players]]\n[[Category:AD Alcorc\u00f3n footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Ja\u00e9n footballers]]\n[[Category:UB Conquense footballers]]\n[[Category:CD Guadalajara (Spain) footballers]]\n[[Category:Granada CF footballers]]\n[[Category:C\u00e1diz CF players]]\n[[Category:UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s players]]\n[[Category:CD Lugo players]]\n[[Category:CD Mirand\u00e9s footballers]]\n[[Category:CF Villanovense players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Spanish name|Serrano|Mac\u00edas}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Juanjo\n| image = \n| full_name = Juan Jos\u00e9 Serrano Mac\u00edas\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1981|10|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Calamonte]], Spain\n| height = 1.84 m\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| currentclub = [[CD Santa Amalia|Santa Amalia]]\n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[M\u00e9rida UD|M\u00e9rida]]\n| years1 = 2000\u20132001 | clubs1 = [[M\u00e9rida UD|M\u00e9rida Promesas]] | caps1 = 36 | goals1 = 26\n| years2 = 2001\u20132003 | clubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B]] | caps2 = 40 | goals2 = 3\n| years3 = 2003\u20132004 | clubs3 = [[AD Alcorc\u00f3n|Alcorc\u00f3n]] | caps3 = 30 | goals3 = 5\n| years4 = 2004\u20132005 | clubs4 = [[CD D\u00edter Zafra|D\u00edter Zafra]] | caps4 = 34 | goals4 = 6\n| years5 = 2005\u20132006 | clubs5 = [[Real Ja\u00e9n|Ja\u00e9n]] | caps5 = 31 | goals5 = 4\n| years6 = 2006\u20132007 | clubs6 = [[UD Lanzarote|Lanzarote]] | caps6 = 36 | goals6 = 14\n| years7 = 2007\u20132008 | clubs7 = [[Mazarr\u00f3n CF|Mazarr\u00f3n]] | caps7 = 33 | goals7 = 3\n| years8 = 2008\u20132009 | clubs8 = [[UB Conquense|Conquense]] | caps8 = 29 | goals8 = 2\n| years9 = 2009\u20132010 | clubs9 = [[CF Villanovense|Villanovense]] | caps9 = 36 | goals9 = 21\n| years10 = 2010\u20132011 | clubs10 = [[CD Guadalajara (Spain)|Guadalajara]] | caps10 = 37 | goals10 = 20\n| years11 = 2011\u20132013 | clubs11 = [[Granada CF|Granada]] | caps11 = 0 | goals11 = 0\n| years12 = 2011\u20132012 | clubs12 = \u2192 [[C\u00e1diz CF|C\u00e1diz]] (loan) | caps12 = 29 | goals12 = 9\n| years13 = 2012\u20132013 | clubs13 = \u2192 [[UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s|Logron\u00e9s]] (loan) | caps13 = 13 | goals13 = 0\n| years14 = 2013 | clubs14 = [[CD Guadalajara (Spain)|Guadalajara]] | caps14 = 16 | goals14 = 4\n| years15 = 2013\u20132014 | clubs15 = [[CD Lugo|Lugo]] | caps15 = 16 | goals15 = 0\n| years16 = 2014\u20132015 | clubs16 = [[CD Mirand\u00e9s|Mirand\u00e9s]] | caps16 = 31 | goals16 = 2\n| years17 = 2015\u20132017 | clubs17 = [[CF Villanovense|Villanovense]] | caps17 = 59 | goals17 = 9\n| years18 = 2017\u2013 | clubs18 = [[CD Santa Amalia|Santa Amalia]] | caps18 = 38 | goals18 = 15\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| club-update = 25 November 2018\n}}\n\n'''Juan Jos\u00e9 Serrano Mac\u00edas''' (born 3 October 1981), commonly known as '''Juanjo''', is a Spanish [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[CD Santa Amalia]] as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]].\n\n==Football career==\nJuanjo was born in [[Calamonte]], [[Province of Badajoz]].  After starting his senior career with local [[M\u00e9rida UD]]'s [[reserve team]], he went on to spend one full decade in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]. He first represented in that level [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B]], [[AD Alcorc\u00f3n]], [[CD D\u00edter Zafra]], [[Real Ja\u00e9n]], [[UD Lanzarote]], [[Mazarr\u00f3n CF]], [[UB Conquense]], [[CF Villanovense]] and [[CD Guadalajara (Spain)|CD Guadalajara]].\n\nJuanjo joined [[La Liga]] club [[Granada CF]] in 2011 but never represented it officially, being loaned to [[C\u00e1diz CF]] and [[UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s]] in the same tier. On 20 January 2013 he terminated his contract and returned to Guadalajara,<ref>[http://www.granadacf.es/index.php?seccion=leer_mas&id_noticia=1382 Juanjo Serrano traspasado al Guadalajara (Juanjo Serrano transferred to Guadalajara)]; Granada CF, 21 January 2013 (in Spanish)</ref> signing a two-and-a-half-year deal.<ref>[http://www.deportivoguadalajara.es/web/juanjo-regresa-al-club-deportivo-guadalajara/ Juanjo regresa al Club Deportivo Guadalajara (Juanjo returns to Club Deportivo Guadalajara)]; CD Guadalajara, 20 January 2013 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nAged already 31, Juanjo made his first appearance in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] on 26 January 2013, starting in a 0\u20132 away loss against [[Girona FC]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/01/26/futbol/2adivision/1359219403.html El Girona rompe la mala racha (Girona end negative streak)]; [[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]], 26 January 2013 (in Spanish)</ref> His first goal with the professionals came on 30 March as he scored the only at [[UD Las Palmas]],<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/03/30/futbol/2adivision/1364670407.html Juanjo silencia a Las Palmas en su estadio (Juanjo silents Las Palmas away)]; Marca, 30 March 2013 (in Spanish)</ref> and he netted a second the following weekend, contributing to a 3\u20131 home success over [[C\u00f3rdoba CF]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/04/07/futbol/2adivision/1365357493.html El Deportivo se aferra a Segunda y apaga las ilusiones del C\u00f3rdoba (Deportivo cling on to ''Segunda'' and dim C\u00f3rdoba's hopes)]; Marca, 7 April 2013 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nOn 23 August 2013, Juanjo moved to fellow league side [[CD Lugo]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/08/23/futbol/equipos/lugo/1377274420.html El Lugo incorpora para el ataque a Juanjo (Lugo add Juanjo to attack)]; Marca, 23 August 2013 (in Spanish)</ref> He totalled only 603 minutes of action in [[2013\u201314 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|his first and only season]], and subsequently joined [[CD Mirand\u00e9s]] also in the second division.<ref>[http://www.cdmirandes.com/-/juan-jose-serrano-macias-juanjo-nuevo-fichaje-del-c-d-mirandes Juan Jos\u00e9 Serrano Macias \"Juanjo\" nuevo fichaje del C.D. Mirand\u00e9s (Juan Jos\u00e9 Serrano Macias \"Juanjo\" new signing of C.D. Mirand\u00e9s)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826121239/http://www.cdmirandes.com/-/juan-jose-serrano-macias-juanjo-nuevo-fichaje-del-c-d-mirandes|date=26 August 2014}}; CD Mirand\u00e9s, 30 June 2014 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|400089}}\n*{{Futbolme|19226}}\n*{{LaPreferente|73601<!-- C7372 -->}}\n*{{Soccerway|juan-jose-serrano-macias/60098}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Juanjo}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Tierra de M\u00e9rida - Vegas Bajas]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Extremaduran footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B players]]\n[[Category:AD Alcorc\u00f3n footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Ja\u00e9n footballers]]\n[[Category:UB Conquense footballers]]\n[[Category:CD Guadalajara (Spain) footballers]]\n[[Category:Granada CF footballers]]\n[[Category:C\u00e1diz CF players]]\n[[Category:UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s players]]\n[[Category:CD Lugo players]]\n[[Category:CD Mirand\u00e9s footballers]]\n[[Category:CF Villanovense players]]\n", "name_user": "Quite A Character", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor tidyups overall, nothing hurt whatsoever.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juanjo_(footballer,_born_1981)"}
{"title_page": "1990 Intercontinental Cup", "text_new": "{{short description|Football match}}\n{{Infobox football match\n|                   title = 1990 Intercontinental Cup\n| image = ToyotaCup1990.jpg\n|                   event =\n|                   team1 = [[A.C. Milan|Milan]]\n|        team1association = {{flagicon|ITA|size=30px}}\n|              team1score = 3\n|                   team2 = [[Club Olimpia|Olimpia]]\n|        team2association = {{flagicon|PAR|1990|size=30px}}\n|              team2score = 0\n|                 details =\n|                    date = 9 December 1990\n|                 stadium = [[National Stadium (Tokyo)|National Stadium]]\n|                    city = [[Tokyo]]\n|      man_of_the_match1a = [[Frank Rijkaard]] ([[A.C. Milan|Milan]])\n| man_of_the_match1atitle =\n|      man_of_the_match1b =\n| man_of_the_match1btitle =\n|                 referee = [[Jos\u00e9 Roberto Wright]] ([[Brazilian Football Confederation|Brazil]])\n|              attendance = 60,228\n|                 weather =\n|                previous = [[1989 Intercontinental Cup|1989]]\n|                    next = [[1991 Intercontinental Cup|1991]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1990 Intercontinental Cup''' was a [[football (soccer)|football]] match played on 9 December 1990 between [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] of [[Italy]], winners of the [[1989\u201390 European Cup|1989\u201390]] [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]], and [[Club Olimpia|Olimpia]] of [[Paraguay]], winners of the [[1990 Copa Libertadores|1990]] [[Copa Libertadores]]. The match was played at the neutral venue of the [[National Stadium (Tokyo)|National Stadium]] in [[Tokyo]] in front of 60,228 fans.<ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.rsssf.com/tablest/toyota90.html\n| title      = Intercontinental Club Cup 1990\n| first      = Josef\n| last       = Bobrowsky\n| publisher  = [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]\n| date       = 2 August 1999\n| accessdate = 27 January 2009\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081224123816/http://www.rsssf.com/tablest/toyota90.html| archivedate= 24 December 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[Frank Rijkaard]] was named as [[man of the match]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablest/toyotamvp.html |title=Toyota Cup - Most Valuable Player of the Match Award |first=Marcelo |last=Leme de Arruda |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] |date=2 January 2009 |accessdate=26 January 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211162554/http://rsssf.com/tablest/toyotamvp.html |archivedate=11 February 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 FIFA Council recognised all the trophy winners as club world champions with the same title to the [[FIFA Club World Cup]] winners, then as official<ref name=\":F152322\">\"Official (''plural'' officials), from the Latin '' offici\u0101lis.'' 1. The official word is also used to refer to what is recognized or derives from an authority. cfr. {{cite web|url=https://www.dictionary.com/browse/official|title=Official, definition|author=dictionary.com}} 2. Approved by the government or someone in power. cfr. {{cite web|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english-spanish/official|title=official|author=dictionary.cambridge.org}} It is synonymous with legal, legitimate, approved. cfr. {{cite web|url=https://www.thesaurus.com/browse/official|title=Synonyms for official|author=thesaurus.com}}</ref><ref name=\":F154232\">For FIFA statute, official competitions are those for representative teams organized by FIFA or any confederation. Representative teams are usually national teams but also club teams that represent a confederation in the interconfederal competitions or a member association in a continental competition cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/the-fifa-statutes-in-force-as-of-27-april-2016-2782908.pdf?cloudid=vga5sv1yxeayptzrdudx|title=FIFA Statutes, April 2016 edition|page=5|format=PDF}} cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/statistical-kit-fifa-club-world-cup-uae-2018.pdf?cloudid=mkbo3nwk4btahl9gwtwl|title=FIFA Club World Cup UAE 2018: Statistical-kit|date=10 December 2018|page=13|format=PDF}} cfr. {{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/Regulations/uefaorg/Regulations/02/55/82/79/2558279_DOWNLOAD.pdf|title=2018/19 UEFA Champions League regulations|page=10}}</ref> \"[[Intercontinental Cup (football)#International participation|world champions]]\" FIFA.<ref name=\":F154233222\">\u201cWhile it does not promote the statistical unification of tournaments, that is, has not absorbed to the Intercontinental Cup (merged with FIFA Club World Cup in 2005), FIFA is the only organization with worldwide jurisdiction over continental confederations and, then, the only one that can confer a title on that level, ergo the title assigned by FIFA with Official Document to the winners of the Intercontinental Cup is legally a FIFA world title.\"  cfr. {{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/the-fifa-statutes-in-force-as-of-27-april-2016-2782908.pdf?cloudid=vga5sv1yxeayptzrdudx|title=FIFA Statutes, April 2016 edition|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=19|format=PDF|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}} cfr.</ref><ref name=\"FIFA201732\">{{cite press release|date=27 October 2017|title=FIFA Council approves key organisational elements of the FIFA World Cup|url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/news/y=2017/m=10/news=fifa-council-approves-key-organisational-elements-of-the-fifa-world-cu-2917722.html|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/fifa-acepta-propuesta-de-conembol-de-reconocer-titulos-de-copa-intercontinental-como-mundiales-de|title=FIFA acepta propuesta de CONMEBOL de reconocer t\u00edtulos de copa intercontinental como mundiales de clubes|date=29 October 2017|publisher=conmebol.com|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=\"kit201822\">{{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/statistical-kit-fifa-club-world-cup-uae-2018.pdf?cloudid=mkbo3nwk4btahl9gwtwl|title=FIFA Club World Cup UAE 2018: Statistical-kit|date=10 December 2018|page=13|format=PDF}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Match details==\n{{footballbox\n|date=9 December 1990\n|time=12:00\n|team1=[[A.C. Milan|Milan]] {{flagicon|ITA}}\n|score=3\u20130\n|report=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/match/3308/\n|team2={{flagicon|PAR|1990}} [[Club Olimpia|Olimpia]]\n|goals1=[[Frank Rijkaard|Rijkaard]] {{goal|43||65}} <br/> [[Giovanni Stroppa|Stroppa]] {{goal|62}}\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[National Stadium (Tokyo)|National Stadium]], [[Tokyo]]\n|attendance=60,228\n|referee= [[Jos\u00e9 Roberto Wright]] ([[Brazilian Football Confederation|Brazil]])}}\n{| width=92% |\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _black_stripes\n | pattern_b  = _milan8991h\n | pattern_ra = _black_stripes\n | pattern_sh = \n| pattern_so = _color_3_stripes_red\n | leftarm    = FF0000\n | body       = FF0000\n | rightarm   = FF0000\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = FFFFFF\n | title      = Milan\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _blackborder\n | pattern_b  = _blackhorizontal\n | pattern_ra = _blackborder\n | leftarm    = FFFFFF\n | body       = FFFFFF\n | rightarm   = FFFFFF\n | pattern_sh =_blackbottom\n | pattern_so = _whitetop\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = 000000\n | title      = Olimpia\n}}\n|}\n{| width=100%\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size:90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|colspan=\"4\"|\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1'''||{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Andrea Pazzagli]]\n|-\n|RB ||'''2'''||{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Mauro Tassotti]]\n|-\n|CB ||'''6'''||{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Franco Baresi]] (C)\n|-\n|CB ||'''5'''||{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Alessandro Costacurta]]\n|-\n|LB ||'''3'''||{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Paolo Maldini]] || || {{suboff|25}}\n|-\n|CM ||'''4'''||{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Angelo Carbone]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''8'''||{{flagicon|NED}} [[Frank Rijkaard]]\n|-\n|RM ||'''7'''||{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Roberto Donadoni]